WEBVTT

00:25.734 --> 00:29.320
And what's the plan?              
              It will only          
              confuse you.

00:29.362 --> 00:32.115
Listen, I can't be                
 any more confused                 
 than I already am.

00:32.156 --> 00:34.993
Steve, I would            
          rather be prosecuting     
          than defending you.

00:35.035 --> 00:37.787
Why?                      
          Because I think           
          you're guilty as hell.

00:37.829 --> 00:40.040
Well, maybe I should              
 get another lawyer then.

00:40.081 --> 00:43.209
Well, I'm not             
          looking forward to        
          twisting the Navy's arm.

00:43.251 --> 00:46.087
Why? What, are you                
 scared of the brass?              
                      Worse.

00:46.129 --> 00:47.839
Respectful.

00:47.881 --> 00:49.841
You know, sometimes I think       
 the Navy's a master plan

00:49.883 --> 00:52.719
designed by geniuses              
 for execution by idiots.

00:52.761 --> 00:55.263
Where did you hear that? 
 I couldn't have just              
 made that up myself?

00:55.305 --> 00:57.390
Could have made up            
      the Gettysburg Address too.   
      Where'd you hear it?

00:57.432 --> 00:59.684
That's one of                     
 Tom Keefer's wisecracks.          
                      Oh.

00:59.726 --> 01:01.519
Thomas Keefer,            
          your novelist friend.     
 Yeah.

01:01.561 --> 01:03.855
He's got the sharpest mind        
 on the ship.                      
          He's sharp, all right.

01:03.897 --> 01:05.690
He knows everything Queeg did.

01:06.316 --> 01:08.068
I'm sure he does.

01:16.743 --> 01:19.996
The trial counsel             
      will state the charge         
      and specification.

01:20.789 --> 01:23.083
Charge one, mutiny.

01:23.124 --> 01:26.711
Violation of Article 94,      
      Uniform Code                  
      of Military Justice.

01:26.753 --> 01:29.506
Specification: In that        
      Lieutenant Stephen Maryk,

01:29.547 --> 01:33.426
while serving             
          as executive officer      
          aboard the USS   Caine,

01:33.468 --> 01:38.181
did on December 18th, 2022,   
      commit an act of mutiny.

01:38.223 --> 01:41.893
Lieutenant Maryk willfully,       
 and without proper authority,

01:41.935 --> 01:44.354
and without                       
 justifiable cause

01:44.395 --> 01:47.273
did relieve from duty         
      Lieutenant Commander          
      Philip Francis Queeg,

01:47.315 --> 01:50.110
then serving                  
      as the duly appointed         
      commanding officer

01:50.151 --> 01:51.485
of the USS   Caine,

01:51.527 --> 01:54.280
who was then                  
      in lawful exercise            
      of his command.

01:55.156 --> 01:56.574
How do you plead?

01:57.158 --> 01:58.326
Not guilty.

01:58.368 --> 02:00.161
Defense will stipulate            
 that Lieutenant Maryk

02:00.203 --> 02:02.580
was serving                       
 as executive officer              
 aboard the USS   Caine,

02:02.622 --> 02:04.332
18 December, 2022.

02:04.374 --> 02:08.086
Trial counsel,                
      you may call                  
      your first witness.

02:09.002 --> 02:11.506
Call Lieutenant Commander Queeg.

02:21.599 --> 02:25.061
Do you solemnly swear         
      that the evidence you give    
      shall be the truth,

02:25.103 --> 02:27.480
the whole truth               
      and nothing but the truth,    
      so help you God?

02:27.522 --> 02:29.149
I do.

02:29.190 --> 02:30.650
Be seated.

02:36.531 --> 02:38.825
[prosecutor]              
          State your name, rank     
          and present position.

02:38.867 --> 02:42.495
Philip Francis Queeg,             
 Lieutenant Commander,             
 United States Navy,

02:42.537 --> 02:46.332
currently attached                
 to Headquarters, Fifth Fleet,     
 awaiting reassignment.

02:47.041 --> 02:49.627
Do you recognize 
                  the accused?

02:49.668 --> 02:51.588
[Queeg] Yes.

02:51.629 --> 02:54.132
Lieutenant Maryk,     
              US Navy.

02:54.174 --> 02:58.553
Commander Queeg,                  
 on December 18th, 2022,

02:58.595 --> 03:00.471
were you in command               
 of the USS   Caine?

03:00.513 --> 03:02.015
Yes, I was.

03:02.515 --> 03:04.767
What type of vessel   
              is the   Caine?

03:04.809 --> 03:08.980
Well, her official            
      designation is an MCM--       
      mine countermeasures ship.

03:09.022 --> 03:11.065
And what is           
              her primary mission?

03:11.107 --> 03:14.485
Well, the   Caine                   
 is designed to detect             
 and neutralize sea-based mines.

03:14.527 --> 03:16.070
We conduct                
          minesweeping operations

03:16.112 --> 03:18.198
as directed anywhere 
              in the Persian Gulf,

03:18.239 --> 03:20.450
with an emphasis              
      on the Straits of Hormuz.

03:20.491 --> 03:24.370
Commander,                
          on December 18th, 2022,

03:24.412 --> 03:26.873
were you relieved of command 
      of the   Caine?

03:26.915 --> 03:28.958
Yes.

03:29.000 --> 03:30.460
By whom?

03:30.501 --> 03:32.503
The accused,          
              Lieutenant Maryk.

03:32.545 --> 03:35.882
[prosecutor] Was this     
          a standard watch change?

03:35.924 --> 03:38.843
No, it was            
              totally irregular.

03:38.885 --> 03:40.720
How would you     
                  describe it?      
                  [scoffs]

03:40.762 --> 03:46.017
Well, the most charitable     
      description would be          
      that it was an incident,

03:46.059 --> 03:48.394
a regrettable incident    
          of the temporary

03:48.436 --> 03:50.980
and total collapse        
          of military discipline.

03:51.022 --> 03:55.151
Commander, please relate      
      all the facts that bear       
      on this unauthorized relief.

03:56.277 --> 03:58.321
Okay, well,

03:58.363 --> 04:01.741
the   Caine   sortied from Bahrain    
 on December 16th.

04:01.783 --> 04:05.453
Our mission was to sweep          
 for mines from the Persian Gulf   
 through the Straits of Hormuz.

04:05.495 --> 04:09.290
When a cyclone came along         
 the operation was canceled,

04:09.332 --> 04:11.626
and the boat                      
 started to maneuver               
 to evade the storm.

04:11.668 --> 04:13.878
The storm                         
 was traveling due west.

04:13.920 --> 04:16.714
[prosecutor]                  
      What was the date and time    
      of that course change?

04:16.755 --> 04:20.051
Well, that would be               
 early morning                     
 of the 18th, ma'am.

04:20.093 --> 04:22.762
And as I say, the storm was       
 pretty bad at that point.

04:22.804 --> 04:24.806
Visibility was almost zero.

04:24.847 --> 04:28.184
Couldn't see                      
 any of the other ships            
 in the detachment.

04:28.226 --> 04:31.145
We were sailing blind through     
 the rain and the spray,

04:31.187 --> 04:32.981
and with the wind                 
 and the sea and all,

04:33.022 --> 04:35.108
we had to maneuver                
 using engines and rudders

04:35.149 --> 04:37.110
to hold the evasion course        
 that had been ordered.

04:37.151 --> 04:39.445
But w-we were doing fine.

04:39.487 --> 04:43.116
My executive officer, however,    
 pretty early in the game,

04:43.157 --> 04:46.119
began to show                     
 unusual symptoms                  
 of nervousness.

04:46.159 --> 04:48.079
What were         
                  these symptoms?

04:48.121 --> 04:50.248
Well, for example, he started     
 talking pretty early--

04:50.290 --> 04:53.960
Couldn't have been more           
 than half an hour after           
 the ship started running south--

04:54.002 --> 04:57.463
that we needed                    
 to operate independently          
 and come around to the north.

04:57.505 --> 04:59.549
Why did he want   
                  to do that?

04:59.590 --> 05:01.676
Well, to give you the picture,    
 the cyclone was coming at us      
 from the east.

05:01.718 --> 05:03.303
We were on                
          the western edge of it,

05:03.344 --> 05:06.264
which means where we were,        
 the wind was from due north.

05:06.306 --> 05:10.768
Now, the   Commodore,   of course,    
 was running south with the wind   
 to get out of the storm's path,

05:10.810 --> 05:14.105
which was in accordance with      
 all existing storm doctrine.

05:14.147 --> 05:18.401
My exec, however,                 
 insisted that our ship            
 was on the verge of foundering

05:18.443 --> 05:20.403
and that we had better            
 turn into the wind,

05:20.445 --> 05:23.406
wh-which was the north,           
 if we were to survive.

05:23.448 --> 05:27.118
Now... [chuckles]                 
 ...of course, we weren't          
 in that bad of shape.

05:27.160 --> 05:29.203
And that's what                   
 I mean by nervousness.

05:29.245 --> 05:31.122
What was your objection   
          to coming north,

05:31.164 --> 05:33.082
as your executive officer     
      suggested?

05:33.124 --> 05:35.668
Well, everything was wrong        
 with that idea                    
 that could be wrong with it.

05:35.710 --> 05:39.881
I mean, in the first place,       
 my orders were to proceed south.

05:39.922 --> 05:42.425
My ship wasn't in danger.     
      It--

05:42.467 --> 05:44.761
It was functioning normally.

05:44.802 --> 05:48.598
Uh, to drop out of station    
      and act independently         
      under those circumstances

05:48.639 --> 05:50.141
is out of the question.

05:50.183 --> 05:52.018
And to come around north

05:52.060 --> 05:54.354
would be to head              
      the ship directly into        
      the heart of the cyclone.

05:54.395 --> 05:59.317
It was a senseless suggestion     
 and, under the circumstances,     
 almost suicidal.

05:59.359 --> 06:02.070
I have since checked          
      all of my decisions           
      of December 18th

06:02.111 --> 06:04.072
with the finest               
      ship handlers I know,

06:04.113 --> 06:06.115
ranking all the way up        
      to rear admiral,

06:06.157 --> 06:10.536
and unanimously they agree    
      that the only course          
      in that situation was south.

06:11.662 --> 06:14.916
[prosecutor]                      
 Commander, your last remark       
 was hearsay.

06:14.957 --> 06:16.459
Oh, I'm-- I'm sorry.

06:16.501 --> 06:18.669
I'm not up                    
      on these legal distinctions

06:18.711 --> 06:20.254
as well as I should be,       
      I guess.

06:20.296 --> 06:22.757
[prosecutor]                      
 It's perfectly all right.

06:22.799 --> 06:25.885
Will defense counsel move         
 to strike out the part of         
 the testimony which was hearsay?

06:25.927 --> 06:27.095
All right, so move.

06:27.136 --> 06:28.971
[prosecutor]                      
 Please continue.

06:29.013 --> 06:32.892
Well, i-it's just that Maryk's    
 insistence on us coming around

06:32.933 --> 06:36.771
became more and more strident     
 as the weather deteriorated.

06:36.813 --> 06:38.898
I finally became          
          concerned about him

06:38.940 --> 06:41.025
when suddenly             
          he moved towards me

06:41.067 --> 06:44.529
and out of the blue said          
 I was on the sick list            
 and that he was relieving me.

06:44.570 --> 06:47.657
I-I-- To be honest,           
      I couldn't believe my ears.

06:47.698 --> 06:49.742
Took me a moment          
          to catch on.

06:49.784 --> 06:52.495
It wasn't until               
      he started shouting orders    
      at the officer of the deck

06:52.537 --> 06:55.415
and started countermanding    
      my instructions

06:55.456 --> 06:59.752
that I-I did begin to         
      realize what was going on.

06:59.794 --> 07:01.504
Commander,                        
 can you recall anything

07:01.546 --> 07:04.549
that could have provoked          
 your executive officer's act?

07:04.590 --> 07:06.509
Truthfully, no.

07:06.551 --> 07:09.429
I don't think                 
      my bearing or manner          
      had anything to do with it.

07:09.470 --> 07:13.182
Look... it was            
          a pretty scary situation 
          in that wheelhouse.

07:13.224 --> 07:16.185
Winds were force ten to 12,   
      screeching and all,

07:16.227 --> 07:18.396
and the waves             
          were mountainous.

07:18.438 --> 07:21.524
The barometer had dropped     
      about as low as it's ever     
      been in US Navy history,

07:21.566 --> 07:24.026
and we took               
          a very bad roll.

07:24.068 --> 07:25.820
And I mean a very bad one.

07:25.862 --> 07:28.030
I've done a lot           
          of North Atlantic         
          rolling too.

07:28.072 --> 07:30.032
I just think that Maryk       
      simply went into a panic.

07:30.074 --> 07:31.742
[prosecutor] 
                      Mmm.

07:31.784 --> 07:34.537
Was the   Caine     
                  in grave danger   
                  at that time?

07:34.579 --> 07:37.874
Well, I-I wouldn't say that, 
      no, ma'am.

07:37.915 --> 07:41.252
I-I thought                       
 we righted ourselves very nicely 
 out of that bad roll.

07:41.294 --> 07:45.715
He repeatedly tried to            
 order me off the bridge,          
 but I stayed right where I was

07:45.756 --> 07:49.260
and gave him orders           
      only as I thought necessary   
      for the safety of the ship.

07:49.302 --> 07:52.972
I-In the situation,               
 I thought that the chief hazard

07:53.014 --> 07:55.975
would be any further          
      act of frenzy on his part.

07:56.017 --> 07:59.979
And to the extent that        
      the   Caine   did come through    
      that storm safely,

08:00.021 --> 08:04.942
despite the unprecedented... 
      [chuckles] ...running amok    
      of my executive officer,

08:04.984 --> 08:09.489
I believe that my handling    
      of the emergency              
      was the correct one.

08:09.530 --> 08:12.658
Did Maryk cite            
          any authority at all      
          when he relieved you?

08:12.700 --> 08:15.036
Oh, he mumbled something          
 about our Article 1108.

08:15.077 --> 08:17.079
I didn't even catch it            
 at the time.

08:17.121 --> 08:20.291
It wasn't till later              
 that he said his authority

08:20.332 --> 08:23.753
was Article 1108          
          of Navy Regulations.

08:23.794 --> 08:26.881
And were you familiar             
 with these articles?              
                  Certainly.

08:26.923 --> 08:29.967
In substance,                     
 what do they provide?

08:30.009 --> 08:33.136
Well, it's my understanding       
 that they make it possible

08:33.179 --> 08:38.726
for the executive officer         
 to relieve the captain            
 i-in an emergency,

08:38.768 --> 08:41.938
a highly unusual emergency        
 where-- where the captain is...

08:41.979 --> 08:43.898
[chuckles]

08:43.940 --> 08:48.319
Well, frankly,                
      where the captain             
      is absolutely unhinged.

08:48.361 --> 08:51.113
Were these articles   
              properly invoked      
              in your situation?

08:51.155 --> 08:54.325
Well, I'm sort of                 
 an interested party here.

08:54.367 --> 08:56.577
But you don't have                
 to take my word for it.

08:56.619 --> 08:59.413
I was successfully            
      conning my ship               
      through that cyclone,

08:59.455 --> 09:02.208
and fortunately for me,           
 I have 130 witnesses              
 of that fact.

09:02.250 --> 09:04.126
Everybody aboard that ship.

09:04.168 --> 09:06.879
Uh, Commander, sorry,     
          there again, sir,

09:06.921 --> 09:09.131
you're testifying     
              to the conclusions    
              of others.

09:09.173 --> 09:11.634
Well, obviously I'm not           
 a legal expert. Sorry.

09:11.676 --> 09:14.929
Strike the witness's      
          last sentence             
          from the record.

09:14.971 --> 09:17.223
Have you ever been    
              mentally ill, sir?

09:17.598 --> 09:19.225
No.

09:19.267 --> 09:21.811
Were you ill in any way       
      when Mr. Maryk relieved you?

09:21.852 --> 09:23.771
I was not.

09:23.813 --> 09:25.565
Did you warn your                 
 executive officer of              
 the consequences of his act?

09:25.606 --> 09:27.984
I told him he was performing 
      a mutinous act.

09:28.025 --> 09:29.944
[prosecutor]                      
 And what was his reply?

09:29.986 --> 09:31.988
He expected to be         
          court-martialed.

09:32.029 --> 09:34.490
He was going                  
      to retain command anyway.

09:36.075 --> 09:38.953
What was the attitude of          
 Lieutenant Junior Grade Keith,    
 the officer of the deck?

09:38.995 --> 09:42.290
Keith was in              
          a state of panic          
          as bad as Maryk's.

09:42.331 --> 09:43.874
[prosecutor]                      
 What was the attitude             
 of the helmsman?

09:43.915 --> 09:46.377
Stilwell                      
      was emotionally unbalanced    
      and for some reason

09:46.419 --> 09:48.963
very devoted to Mr. Keith.

09:49.005 --> 09:50.923
They both backed Maryk.

09:50.965 --> 09:53.634
Is there anything else,       
      Commander Queeg,              
      that you would care to state

09:53.676 --> 09:56.762
in connection with the events     
 of December 18th                  
 aboard the   Caine?

09:56.804 --> 09:58.764
[exhales] Well, I just...

09:59.974 --> 10:02.435
I've thought a lot about      
      all of this, obviously.

10:02.476 --> 10:05.187
It's the gravest occurrence   
      in my career.

10:05.229 --> 10:08.274
The only questionable one     
      I-I'm aware of.

10:10.651 --> 10:13.029
I-I just think that           
      if the officer of the deck

10:13.070 --> 10:16.198
had been anyone               
      other than this               
      immature Mr. Keith

10:16.240 --> 10:18.409
and the helmsman              
      anyone other than Stilwell,

10:18.451 --> 10:20.286
then none of this         
          would have happened.

10:20.328 --> 10:25.458
I mean, a competent officer   
      would have repudiated         
      Maryk's orders

10:25.499 --> 10:28.085
and a normal sailor       
          at the helm

10:28.127 --> 10:31.881
would have disregarded        
      both of those officers        
      and obeyed me.

10:32.840 --> 10:36.302
It was just bad luck          
      that these three men,

10:36.344 --> 10:38.888
Maryk, Keith              
          and Stilwell,

10:38.929 --> 10:42.016
combined against me           
      at such a crucial time.

10:43.184 --> 10:44.769
Bad luck for me

10:44.810 --> 10:47.146
and I'm afraid                
      even worse luck for them.

10:47.188 --> 10:49.815
[officer] The court       
          would like to             
          question the witness.

10:51.192 --> 10:53.152
Commander Queeg,

10:53.194 --> 10:56.822
you've taken                  
      all the prescribed physical   
      and mental examinations

10:56.864 --> 10:59.617
incident to entrance to   
          the academy, graduation,

10:59.659 --> 11:01.410
commissioning, promotion 
          and so forth?

11:01.452 --> 11:04.163
Yes, sir, for 21 years.

11:04.205 --> 11:08.167
Does your medical record          
 contain any history of illness,   
 mental or physical?

11:08.209 --> 11:10.127
No, sir, it does not.

11:10.169 --> 11:13.214
Have you ever had             
      an unsatisfactory fitness     
      report, Commander Queeg?

11:13.255 --> 11:15.675
Negative, sir.

11:15.716 --> 11:19.845
Commander, can you account for    
 Lieutenant Maryk's opinion        
 that you were mentally ill?

11:19.887 --> 11:22.098
[chuckles]                    
      All I can say, sir,

11:22.139 --> 11:27.186
is that I assumed command         
 over an extremely...              
 disorganized and dirty ship,

11:27.228 --> 11:32.108
and that's not a reflection       
 on the officer that I relieved.

11:32.149 --> 11:34.527
The   Caine   had gone through    
      a year and a half             
      of arduous duty

11:34.568 --> 11:36.779
a-and it was understandable.

11:36.821 --> 11:42.785
But still, for the safety     
      of that ship and its crew,    
      it demanded to be shaped up,

11:42.827 --> 11:44.995
and I took a lot          
          of strong measures,

11:45.037 --> 11:48.708
a-and Lieutenant Maryk    
          did not see eye to eye    
          with me at all

11:48.749 --> 11:52.461
on this idea              
          of making the   Caine       
          a tight ship again.

11:54.463 --> 11:57.550
[chuckles]            
              Well, maybe--

11:57.591 --> 12:00.803
maybe he thought I was crazy 
      to keep trying.

12:00.845 --> 12:05.349
Anyway, that's                
      the picture of it, sir.

12:05.391 --> 12:08.144
[officer] Thank you. 
              [prosecutor]          
              Your witness.

12:08.185 --> 12:10.896
Commander Queeg,                  
 I would like to ask you

12:10.938 --> 12:14.734
whether you have                  
 ever heard the expression         
 "Old Yellowstain."

12:16.444 --> 12:18.863
In which connection?

12:18.904 --> 12:20.573
Old Yellowstain, sir.

12:22.908 --> 12:24.660
No, I have not.

12:24.702 --> 12:27.580
You weren't aware                 
 that all the officers             
 of the   Caine

12:27.621 --> 12:30.332
habitually referred to you        
 as Old Yellowstain?

12:30.374 --> 12:33.419
I object to the question.         
 Impertinent badgering             
 of the witness.

12:33.461 --> 12:36.422
How does Defense Counsel      
      Greenwald justify             
      this line of questioning?

12:36.464 --> 12:38.257
Please the court,                 
 the nickname Old Yellowstain,

12:38.299 --> 12:39.925
used by the officers      
          of the   Caine,

12:39.967 --> 12:43.095
will be relevant          
          to the issue              
          of mental competence.

12:43.137 --> 12:48.017
Before ruling, the court wishes   
 to caution defense counsel.

12:48.976 --> 12:52.438
This is a most unusual            
 and delicate case.

12:52.480 --> 12:54.440
The honor and career              
 of an officer

12:54.482 --> 12:59.445
with an unblemished               
 military record of 21 years       
 standing is involved.

12:59.487 --> 13:02.031
The defense counsel           
      will have to bear             
      full responsibility

13:02.072 --> 13:03.741
for the conduct           
          of this case.

13:06.577 --> 13:08.746
Subject to                    
      the foregoing comment,

13:09.872 --> 13:12.458
the trial counsel's objection     
 is overruled.

13:13.375 --> 13:16.045
Court stenographer            
      will repeat the question.

13:16.086 --> 13:18.631
"You aren't aware, then,      
      that all the officers         
      of the   Caine

13:18.672 --> 13:21.258
have habitually           
          referred to you           
          as Old Yellowstain?"

13:25.179 --> 13:27.306
I was not aware of that.

13:27.348 --> 13:29.725
No further questions.

13:29.767 --> 13:31.310
For now.

13:31.352 --> 13:34.647
Commander Queeg will be called    
 as a witness for the defense.

13:35.314 --> 13:36.982
For the defense?

13:37.024 --> 13:38.734
Yes, sir.

13:40.361 --> 13:42.530
You're excused,           
          subject to recall.

13:43.322 --> 13:44.657
Thank you, sir.

13:44.698 --> 13:46.826
[prosecutor]                      
 Call Lieutenant Thomas Keefer.

13:51.664 --> 13:53.790
State your name, rank     
          and present station.

13:53.833 --> 13:55.835
Thomas Keefer, Lieutenant,        
 United States Navy,

13:55.876 --> 13:58.170
communication officer             
 of the USS   Caine.

13:58.212 --> 14:00.714
If you recognize 
                  the accused,      
                  state his name.

14:00.756 --> 14:04.009
Lieutenant Steve Maryk,           
 executive officer                 
 of the   Caine.

14:04.051 --> 14:06.387
What is your occupation   
          in civilian life?

14:06.428 --> 14:08.305
I'm a writer.

14:08.347 --> 14:10.724
And has any of your work 
          been published?

14:10.766 --> 14:14.436
A number of short stories         
 have been published, yes, ma'am.

14:14.478 --> 14:18.732
Did you do any writing    
          in your spare time        
          while in service?

14:18.774 --> 14:21.610
Yes, I have completed             
 half a war novel.

14:21.652 --> 14:23.445
[chuckles]                
          And what's the title?

14:23.487 --> 14:25.739
Multitudes, Multitudes.

14:25.781 --> 14:28.450
And has this novel,   
              though incomplete,

14:28.492 --> 14:30.953
recently been accepted    
          by a publisher?

14:30.995 --> 14:32.371
Yes.

14:33.581 --> 14:35.290
Now, Lieutenant Keefer,

14:35.332 --> 14:37.877
were you serving          
          aboard the   Caine          
          in your present capacity

14:37.918 --> 14:40.129
on December 18th,     
              2022?                 
          Yes.

14:40.170 --> 14:42.381
Was Captain Queeg         
          relieved of his command   
          on that date?

14:42.423 --> 14:43.966
He was.                   
                      By whom?

14:44.008 --> 14:45.551
The executive officer.

14:45.593 --> 14:47.720
Describe how you learned 
          that the captain          
          had been relieved.

14:47.761 --> 14:52.349
Uh, well, Mr. Maryk               
 passed word for all officers      
 to come up to the wheelhouse.

14:52.391 --> 14:56.312
When we got there, he told us     
 that the captain was sick         
 and he had assumed command.

14:56.353 --> 15:00.316
Did Captain Queeg         
          show any external signs   
          of being sick?

15:00.357 --> 15:02.067
Look, at the height               
 of a cyclone--

15:02.109 --> 15:04.403
Was he raving,            
          or was he foaming, or--   
 No, no.

15:04.445 --> 15:07.239
Did he look any worse off     
      than, say, Lieutenant Keith? 
      No.

15:07.281 --> 15:08.699
Or Maryk?             
      No.

15:08.741 --> 15:12.244
W-We were all tired,              
 dripping and wiped out.

15:12.286 --> 15:15.122
Mr. Keefer,               
          did you make any effort   
          to persuade Mr. Maryk

15:15.164 --> 15:16.790
to restore Queeg          
          to command?

15:16.832 --> 15:18.584
No, I did not.

15:18.626 --> 15:20.461
Did you not feel 
                  the seriousness   
                  of the moment?

15:20.502 --> 15:21.754
I certainly did.

15:21.795 --> 15:23.797
Why did you take      
              no remedial action?

15:23.839 --> 15:26.967
I wasn't present                  
 when the captain was relieved.

15:27.009 --> 15:29.845
Maryk was in full command.        
 The entire ship was               
 obeying his orders.

15:29.887 --> 15:32.389
I thought that,                   
 for the safety of the ship,

15:32.431 --> 15:34.808
my best course was                
 to obey his orders.

15:34.850 --> 15:36.810
Mr. Keefer, were you 
              aboard the   Caine

15:36.852 --> 15:39.313
throughout the period     
          that Captain Queeg        
          was in command?

15:39.355 --> 15:43.067
Yes, I was.                       
      Did you ever observe any      
      evidence of insanity in him?

15:43.108 --> 15:45.736
I don't--                         
 I can't answer that question,     
 not being a psychiatrist.

15:45.778 --> 15:47.863
Did you ever think        
          he might be insane?

15:47.905 --> 15:49.782
Objection.

15:49.823 --> 15:53.118
Witness is not an expert      
      and matters of opinion        
      are not admissible evidence.

15:53.160 --> 15:54.703
I withdraw the question.

15:54.745 --> 15:58.123
Mr. Keefer,               
          at any time prior         
          to December 18th,

15:58.165 --> 16:01.543
were you informed             
      that Maryk suspected Queeg    
      of being mentally ill?

16:01.585 --> 16:04.296
Yes, I was.                   
          Describe                  
          how you learned this.

16:04.338 --> 16:05.756
Well, uh, let me see.

16:05.798 --> 16:08.509
Two-- Two weeks                   
 before the cyclone,

16:08.550 --> 16:10.594
Maryk showed me                   
 a medical log

16:10.636 --> 16:13.222
he had kept on                    
 Captain Queeg's behavior.

16:13.263 --> 16:16.725
He asked me to come with him      
 to report the situation to--

16:16.767 --> 16:18.978
to Admiral Williams,              
 Commander Fifth Fleet.

16:19.019 --> 16:21.397
And did you consent   
              to go with him?

16:21.438 --> 16:23.023
Yes, I did.               
                              Why?

16:23.065 --> 16:25.317
He was my superior officer        
 and also my close friend.

16:25.359 --> 16:29.154
Did you believe               
      that Maryk's log justified    
      the relief of Queeg?

16:29.196 --> 16:30.781
No. No.

16:30.823 --> 16:32.783
As soon as we got aboard          
 Admiral Williams's ship,

16:32.825 --> 16:35.869
I told him as forcibly        
      as I could that,              
      in my opinion,

16:35.911 --> 16:38.539
the log wouldn't              
      justify the action.

16:38.580 --> 16:42.292
What was his response?    
 After a lot of arguing,           
 he told me--

16:42.334 --> 16:46.797
[clears throat]                   
 After a lot of arguing,           
 he-- he followed my advice.

16:46.839 --> 16:48.716
We returned to the   Caine.

16:48.757 --> 16:52.845
Were you surprised        
          two weeks later when he   
          relieved the captain?

16:53.887 --> 16:55.180
I was stunned.

16:56.056 --> 16:58.559
Were you good with that, 
          Mr. Keefer?

16:59.309 --> 17:01.103
I was badly disturbed.

17:01.145 --> 17:03.939
I thought that, at best,          
 he would be involved              
 in grave difficulties.

17:03.981 --> 17:07.776
I thought it was                  
 a terrible situation              
 and an error on his part.

17:08.569 --> 17:10.112
No further questions.

17:10.154 --> 17:11.571
No questions.

17:11.613 --> 17:14.157
Does the defense intend           
 to recall this witness

17:14.199 --> 17:15.159
at a later time?

17:15.200 --> 17:16.785
No, sir.

17:16.827 --> 17:19.997
No cross-examination of this      
 highly material witness?

17:20.039 --> 17:21.123
No, sir.

17:22.958 --> 17:25.044
The court                         
 will question the witness.

17:26.252 --> 17:27.503
Mr. Keefer--                  
      [clears throat]

17:27.546 --> 17:30.924
Now, as to this                   
 so-called medical log,

17:30.966 --> 17:33.844
the facts it contained            
 which convinced Lieutenant Maryk

17:33.886 --> 17:36.305
that he should                    
 report the captain                
 to Admiral Williams

17:36.346 --> 17:37.639
didn't convince you.

17:37.681 --> 17:39.391
Is that right?                    
              They did not, sir.

17:39.433 --> 17:41.185
Why not?

17:41.226 --> 17:44.104
Sir, it's not something a layman 
 can intelligently discuss.

17:44.146 --> 17:46.815
You've stated                     
 you're a close friend             
 of Mr. Maryk.

17:46.857 --> 17:48.442
Yes, sir.

17:48.484 --> 17:51.236
Well, this court                  
 is trying to find out,            
 among other things,

17:51.278 --> 17:54.573
any possible                      
 extenuating circumstances         
 for his acts.

17:54.615 --> 17:56.575
Did this medical log              
 merely indicate to you

17:56.617 --> 17:59.745
that Captain Queeg                
 was a highly normal               
 and competent officer?

17:59.787 --> 18:01.997
Sir,                      
          speaking from ignorance,

18:02.039 --> 18:06.794
it's always seemed to me      
      that mental disability        
      was a-- a relative thing.

18:06.835 --> 18:09.379
Captain Queeg was             
      a very strict disciplinarian

18:09.421 --> 18:12.549
and extremely meticulous 
          in hunting down           
          the smallest matters.

18:12.591 --> 18:16.512
He wasn't the easiest person 
      in the world to reason with.

18:16.553 --> 18:19.640
And there were several occasions 
 where I thought                   
 he came down too hard

18:19.681 --> 18:22.392
and spent excessive time 
          on small matters.

18:22.434 --> 18:24.812
They were very unpleasant.

18:24.853 --> 18:28.899
But to jump from them         
      to the conclusion that        
      the captain was a maniac,

18:28.941 --> 18:31.485
no, no, I was compelled, 
          in all honesty,

18:31.527 --> 18:33.737
to warn Maryk         
              against doing that.

18:34.947 --> 18:37.407
[prosecutor] State your name,     
 rank and present station.

18:37.449 --> 18:39.034
[clears throat]

18:39.076 --> 18:42.538
Junius Urban,                 
      Quartermaster Third Class,    
      US Navy

18:42.579 --> 18:44.581
of the USS   Caine.

18:46.542 --> 18:48.627
Do you recognize                  
 the accused?

18:49.461 --> 18:50.712
Ma'am?

18:50.754 --> 18:52.965
Do you recognize                  
 the accused?

18:54.508 --> 18:55.926
M-Ma'am?

18:57.094 --> 19:00.597
Do you recognize                  
 the officer                       
 at that table?

19:01.598 --> 19:04.226
[Urban]           
                  Wh-Which one?     
                  There are two.

19:04.268 --> 19:06.562
Name the one you recognize.

19:07.396 --> 19:09.106
Th-That's the exec.

19:09.148 --> 19:11.108
What's his name?

19:11.150 --> 19:12.651
M-Mr. Maryk.

19:12.693 --> 19:14.945
What is he                        
 the exec of?

19:15.737 --> 19:16.989
The-- The ship.

19:17.030 --> 19:20.325
Name the ship.                    
          The   Caine.

19:20.367 --> 19:22.953
Thank you.    
 Sorry.

19:22.995 --> 19:25.706
Urban,                        
      on December 18th, 2022,

19:25.747 --> 19:27.958
were you serving                  
 aboard the   Caine                  
 in your present capacity?

19:28.000 --> 19:30.252
Is that                       
      the day it happened?

19:30.294 --> 19:32.421
The day           
                  what happened?

19:32.462 --> 19:34.173
I don't know.

19:34.214 --> 19:36.967
That was the day      
              of the cyclone, yes.

19:37.009 --> 19:39.178
Sure.                     
          I-- I was aboard.

19:40.345 --> 19:41.847
Were you              
              in the wheelhouse

19:41.889 --> 19:44.516
when Mr. Maryk            
          relieved Captain Queeg?

19:44.558 --> 19:46.059
Yes.

19:46.101 --> 19:48.103
Who else                  
          was in the wheelhouse     
          at the time?

19:48.145 --> 19:53.734
Well, um, there was--         
      there was the captain         
      and M-Mr. Maryk.

19:54.568 --> 19:55.861
Yes?

19:55.903 --> 19:57.779
Th-Th-The helmsman.

19:57.821 --> 19:59.948
His name?         
 Stilwell.

19:59.990 --> 20:01.033
Who else?

20:01.074 --> 20:02.659
The officer of the day.       
 His name?

20:02.701 --> 20:03.994
Mr. Keith.

20:04.036 --> 20:06.413
What were you doing   
              in the wheelhouse?

20:06.455 --> 20:08.707
I had the watch.

20:08.749 --> 20:10.959
Urban,                        
      describe in your own words

20:11.001 --> 20:13.712
how Lieutenant Maryk          
      relieved the captain.

20:16.340 --> 20:17.883
H-He said...

20:18.759 --> 20:21.553
"I relieve you," ma'am.

20:21.595 --> 20:23.889
What was happening    
              at the time?

20:23.931 --> 20:27.100
Well, the ship                    
 was rolling very bad.             
 It was an ass-kicker storm.

20:28.101 --> 20:30.520
Urban, describe everything        
 that happened

20:30.562 --> 20:34.650
in the ten minutes                
 before Captain Queeg              
 was relieved.

20:34.691 --> 20:37.569
Well, li-like I say,

20:37.611 --> 20:40.072
the ship                  
          was rolling very bad.

20:41.198 --> 20:42.741
That's all?

20:42.783 --> 20:45.702
Did the captain say anything?     
 Did the exec say anything?

20:45.744 --> 20:47.579
Did the officer of the day        
 say anything?

20:47.621 --> 20:50.249
Or did the ship                   
 just roll in silence              
 for ten minutes?

20:50.290 --> 20:52.417
Well, ma'am,          
              it was a cyclone.

20:52.459 --> 20:57.047
Petty Officer Urban,      
          you are under oath.

20:57.089 --> 20:58.757
W-Well...

21:00.092 --> 21:03.679
I-I think the captain             
 wanted to come north,

21:03.720 --> 21:05.931
and the exec wanted               
 to come s-south.

21:05.973 --> 21:08.183
O-Or the other way around,        
 or something like that.

21:08.225 --> 21:10.394
[prosecutor]                      
 Why did the captain               
 want to come south?

21:10.435 --> 21:12.396
I don't know.                 
 Why did the exec                  
 want to come north?

21:12.437 --> 21:15.190
Ma'am, I'm just                   
 a third-class petty officer.

21:15.232 --> 21:18.026
Did the captain   
                  act crazy?        
 No.

21:18.068 --> 21:19.695
Did the execs     
                  seem scared?      
 N-No.

21:19.736 --> 21:21.280
Did the captain? 
 No.

21:21.321 --> 21:22.864
Did anyone?

21:23.949 --> 21:26.952
I-- I was goddamn scared.

21:27.661 --> 21:29.579
I-I beg your pardon, sir.

21:29.621 --> 21:33.417
But the captain               
      did not act crazy in any way 
      that morning, correct?

21:33.458 --> 21:36.253
The captain                       
 was the same as always.           
          Crazy or sane, Urban?

21:36.295 --> 21:38.463
H-He was sane.

21:38.505 --> 21:40.799
S-S-S-So far as I knew.

21:40.841 --> 21:43.802
Petty Officer Urban, 
              how old are you?

21:43.844 --> 21:46.388
Twenty.                           
                  What schooling    
                  have you had?

21:46.430 --> 21:49.516
[stammering] High school--        
 High school diploma.

21:49.558 --> 21:51.977
[officer]                 
          Have you been telling     
          the whole truth here,

21:52.019 --> 21:53.729
or haven't you?

21:55.355 --> 22:00.193
Sir, a-an enlisted man            
 o-on watch

22:00.235 --> 22:03.947
isn't supposed to listen          
 to arguments between              
 the captain and the exec.

22:04.656 --> 22:06.199
Did you like the captain?

22:07.409 --> 22:09.036
S-Sure, I liked him, sir.

22:09.077 --> 22:11.538
Continue              
              your examination.

22:11.580 --> 22:13.290
No further questions.

22:13.332 --> 22:16.209
Petty Officer Urban,          
      were you aboard the   Caine

22:16.251 --> 22:18.337
when she cut                  
      her own tow cable?

22:18.378 --> 22:20.130
Y-Yes-- Yes, sir.

22:20.172 --> 22:22.966
And what were you             
      doing at the time?            
                          I was--

22:23.008 --> 22:27.012
Well, that is, the captain    
      was bawling me out            
      on the bridge, sir.

22:27.054 --> 22:29.348
What for?                         
          My shirttail was out.

22:29.389 --> 22:32.517
Was the captain               
      very strict on the subject    
      of shirttails?

22:32.559 --> 22:35.270
[chuckles] Yes, sir.              
 He was very strict                
 on shirttails, sir.

22:35.312 --> 22:37.189
And while he was 
                  describing        
                  your shirttail,

22:37.230 --> 22:39.191
the ship went around 
              in a full circle

22:39.232 --> 22:40.984
and steamed over      
              its own tow cable.

22:41.026 --> 22:43.195
Is that what happened?    
 I object to this                  
 line of questioning.

22:43.236 --> 22:45.364
Counsel has                       
 tricked the witness               
 with leading questions

22:45.405 --> 22:48.116
into asserting that the   Caine     
 cut its own tow line,

22:48.158 --> 22:51.203
a material point                  
 that was not touched upon         
 in direct examination.

22:51.244 --> 22:53.205
Please the court,         
          the witness has stated

22:53.246 --> 22:55.165
that he's never       
              seen the captain      
              do anything crazy.

22:55.207 --> 22:57.542
I'm simply trying             
      to refute that statement.

22:57.584 --> 23:01.463
Defense counsel                   
 will have the opportunity         
 to originate evidence later.

23:01.505 --> 23:03.423
Objection sustained.

23:03.465 --> 23:06.885
Cross-examination thus far    
      will be stricken              
      from the record.

23:08.220 --> 23:10.847
Urban, what is            
          a paranoid personality?

23:10.889 --> 23:12.432
Huh?                              
          A paranoid personality.

23:12.474 --> 23:14.142
What is it?   
 Sir?

23:14.184 --> 23:16.520
Would you recognize   
              a psychotic person    
              if you saw one?

23:16.561 --> 23:17.896
Me?               
 It's okay.

23:17.938 --> 23:20.023
No further questions.             
 Thank you.

23:20.065 --> 23:22.234
Petty Officer Urban,

23:22.275 --> 23:25.821
you will not discuss              
 your testimony in this courtroom 
 with anybody, understand?

23:25.862 --> 23:28.240
Wh-Who, sir?              
          Me, sir?

23:28.657 --> 23:29.658
No, sir.

23:29.699 --> 23:31.451
Witness excused.

23:32.077 --> 23:33.578
Thank you, sir.

23:35.288 --> 23:37.332
[whispering]

23:37.374 --> 23:39.584
I see that,                       
 uh, trial counsel                 
 intends to call

23:39.626 --> 23:41.711
a dozen members                   
 of the crew of the   Caine.

23:41.753 --> 23:43.213
Yeah?                             
      Yeah, that's correct.

23:43.255 --> 23:45.215
And the purpose is to confirm     
 Urban's testimony

23:45.257 --> 23:47.342
no one ever                       
 saw the captain                   
 do anything crazy.

23:47.384 --> 23:49.928
That is the purpose.      
 Okay, I'll concede that.

23:49.970 --> 23:52.264
I'll concede                      
 they'll all corroborate           
 Urban's testimony

23:52.305 --> 23:57.436
if you concede that none of them 
 know any more about a paranoid    
 than Urban does.

23:57.477 --> 23:59.896
Yeah, I'll gladly             
      accept that concession        
      on those terms, sir.

23:59.938 --> 24:02.315
Okay.                             
          Lieutenant, that's        
          a weighty concession.

24:02.357 --> 24:05.402
And by your leave, sir,           
 I'll make that concession.

24:05.444 --> 24:07.279
Uh-- [exhales]

24:07.320 --> 24:10.782
Mr. Greenwald, I understand   
      that you were appointed       
      as defense counsel

24:10.824 --> 24:12.200
by the judge advocate.

24:12.242 --> 24:13.577
Yes, sir.

24:13.618 --> 24:15.996
When were you     
                  appointed?        
 Four days ago, sir.

24:16.037 --> 24:19.207
Do you feel you've had enough     
 time to prepare your case?        
 Yes, sir.

24:19.249 --> 24:21.251
Did you undertake     
              the assignment        
              willingly?

24:21.293 --> 24:23.336
Uh, sir,                      
      Lieutenant Greenwald          
      accepted the assignment

24:23.378 --> 24:25.589
at the request                
      of the judge advocate.

24:26.882 --> 24:30.385
[sighs] I see that        
          you're a naval aviator.   
 Yes, sir.

24:30.427 --> 24:33.388
What do you fly? 
 Primarily                         
 the F/A-18 Super Hornet, sir.

24:33.430 --> 24:36.308
Why aren't you    
                  flying now?       
 Medical leave, sir.

24:36.349 --> 24:39.227
Why?      
 Forced to eject                   
 from a damaged aircraft.

24:39.269 --> 24:40.937
I see.

24:40.979 --> 24:44.191
Did you have a chance     
          to practice much law?     
 A little, sir.

24:45.609 --> 24:46.651
[sighs]

24:46.693 --> 24:48.445
Lieutenant Maryk.

24:48.487 --> 24:50.489
Yes, sir.

24:50.530 --> 24:52.908
I need to know if you're      
      happy with your counsel's     
      conduct of the defense.

24:52.949 --> 24:55.494
Sir, if he answers                
 that question,                    
 he does on blind faith.

24:55.535 --> 24:57.954
Can I just have a moment          
 to speak to my client privately?

24:57.996 --> 25:00.248
[sighs]

25:00.957 --> 25:02.083
Two minutes.

25:02.125 --> 25:03.502
[Greenwald]   
                      Come on.

25:03.960 --> 25:05.337
Thank you.

25:07.130 --> 25:09.424
So, do you want           
          to get rid of me?

25:10.467 --> 25:11.968
I don't know.

25:13.053 --> 25:15.347
I think I'm screwed               
 at this point.

25:15.388 --> 25:17.349
Fifteen years                     
 in the brig?

25:17.390 --> 25:19.184
Mm-hmm.

25:20.727 --> 25:23.522
Tell me one thing.                
 Why didn't you                    
 cross-examine Tom?

25:23.563 --> 25:25.857
I don't have time         
          to tell you everything.

25:25.899 --> 25:28.568
Tom Keefer knows everything       
 the captain did. Everything.      
              I'm sure he does.

25:28.610 --> 25:30.487
If he wouldn't talk,              
 it's up to you                    
 to drag it out.

25:30.529 --> 25:32.614
Wasn't it?                        
          You don't understand.

25:32.656 --> 25:34.407
No, I don't understand            
 what you're doing.                
 That's for sure.

25:34.449 --> 25:35.909
I want to fight           
          this case.                
 Why?

25:35.951 --> 25:37.619
Because                   
          I want to win it.         
      Why?

25:37.661 --> 25:39.538
Is that not enough?

25:39.579 --> 25:41.248
Before you said you'd             
 rather be prosecuting             
 than defending me.

25:41.289 --> 25:42.999
So maybe this is                  
 your bizarre way                  
 of prosecuting.

25:43.041 --> 25:46.169
Steve, listen to me   
              very carefully.

25:46.211 --> 25:48.964
Implicating Keefer        
          harms you.                
      What?

25:49.005 --> 25:52.342
Two disgruntled bastards      
      instead of one heroic exec.

25:52.384 --> 25:55.637
I have a chance           
          with one heroic exec.

25:55.679 --> 25:58.974
Making that stick     
              is the only chance    
              for you to win.

26:05.063 --> 26:07.524
For the record,                   
 the court asks the accused,

26:07.566 --> 26:09.985
are you satisfied             
      with your counsel?

26:11.653 --> 26:13.530
I'm satisfied, sir.

26:13.572 --> 26:16.408
Court will not            
          reopen this question.     
 I understand that, sir.

26:16.449 --> 26:19.077
I'm satisfied                 
      with Lieutenant Greenwald.

26:19.119 --> 26:21.705
Proceed with your case,   
          Commander Challee.

26:22.664 --> 26:24.249
Call Lieutenant Keith.

26:33.466 --> 26:35.427
State your name, rank             
 and present station.

26:35.468 --> 26:38.555
Willis Keith,             
          US Navy Junior Grade,

26:38.597 --> 26:40.682
assistant communications officer 
 on the USS   Caine.

26:40.724 --> 26:43.184
Mr. Keith, were you               
 officer of the deck of the   Caine

26:43.226 --> 26:45.395
on December 18th, 2022?

26:45.437 --> 26:46.813
I was.

26:46.855 --> 26:49.524
Was the captain relieved      
      of his command on that date?

26:49.566 --> 26:50.609
Yes, ma'am.

26:50.650 --> 26:52.193
Do you know why           
          the executive officer

26:52.235 --> 26:53.612
relieved the captain?     
 Yes.

26:53.653 --> 26:56.740
Captain Queeg                 
      had lost control of himself

26:56.781 --> 26:59.534
and the ship              
          was in grave danger       
          of foundering.

27:00.619 --> 27:02.203
How many years            
          have you served at sea,   
          Lieutenant?

27:02.245 --> 27:04.164
One year, three months.

27:04.205 --> 27:06.207
Do you know how many years    
      Commander Queeg               
      has served at sea?

27:06.249 --> 27:08.168
I guess about 17 years.

27:08.209 --> 27:10.128
Which one of you is           
      better qualified to judge

27:10.170 --> 27:12.714
whether a ship            
          is foundering or not?

27:12.756 --> 27:14.758
Myself, ma'am,

27:14.799 --> 27:17.344
if I'm in possession          
      of my faculties               
      and Commander Queeg isn't.

27:17.385 --> 27:19.220
Well, what makes you think        
 he wasn't in possession           
 of his faculties?

27:19.262 --> 27:21.473
He wasn't on the morning 
          of December 18th.

27:21.514 --> 27:24.643
Oh. Have you studied      
          medicine or psychiatry?   
 No.

27:24.684 --> 27:29.105
Did the captain foam or rave 
      or make insane gestures?

27:29.147 --> 27:32.901
No. No.                           
 What he did do was just as bad.

27:32.942 --> 27:34.069
Clarify that, will you?

27:34.110 --> 27:36.321
His orders were vague.

27:36.363 --> 27:39.783
He insisted on going south        
 when we had a north wind          
 of 90 miles an hour behind us.

27:39.824 --> 27:42.535
With a stern wind that strong,    
 the ship couldn't be controlled.

27:42.577 --> 27:45.705
In your expert opinion        
      as ship handler, that is.

27:45.747 --> 27:49.125
Well, Steve Maryk thought so,     
 and he's an expert ship handler.

27:49.167 --> 27:53.797
Were you completely loyal     
      to your captain or not,       
      prior to 18 December?

27:53.838 --> 27:58.635
I was, uh, antagonistic       
      to Captain Queeg              
      at certain isolated times.

27:58.677 --> 28:00.679
At what isolated times    
          were you antagonistic?

28:00.720 --> 28:03.098
When the captain          
          mistreated his men,       
          I opposed him.

28:03.139 --> 28:04.808
When did the captain      
          ever mistreat his men?

28:04.849 --> 28:07.936
Well, for one thing,              
 he systematically persecuted

28:07.977 --> 28:09.854
Gunners Mate Second Class         
 Stilwell.

28:09.896 --> 28:11.981
In what way?

28:12.023 --> 28:15.068
First, he restricted him      
      to the ship for six months    
      for reading on watch.

28:15.110 --> 28:17.987
Refused to grant him leave        
 when we were back in the States   
 in December 2021.

28:18.029 --> 28:22.867
The man was getting           
      anonymous messages about      
      his wife's infidelity.

28:22.909 --> 28:26.037
[stammers, sighs]             
      Maryk gave Stilwell           
      a 72-hour emergency leave.

28:26.079 --> 28:27.872
He returned a few hours       
      over leave--

28:27.914 --> 28:31.793
Hold on. Hold on.         
          You say that Maryk        
          gave Stilwell leave.

28:33.503 --> 28:35.922
Did Maryk know that the captain   
 had denied Stilwell leave?

28:35.964 --> 28:37.799
Yes.

28:37.841 --> 28:41.177
Did Maryk check with the captain 
 before authorizing this leave?

28:41.219 --> 28:43.138
No, um...

28:43.179 --> 28:45.640
Are you testifying,   
              Mr. Keith,

28:45.682 --> 28:48.852
that Maryk                
          deliberately violated     
          his captain's orders?

28:50.937 --> 28:52.355
Uh...

28:53.732 --> 28:57.694
I-- I mean,                   
      i-it was my fault, actually.

28:57.736 --> 28:59.696
'Cause I begged him to.   
          He was--

28:59.738 --> 29:01.990
Mr. Keith, we now             
      have your testimony

29:02.031 --> 29:03.992
that you and Stilwell     
          and Maryk

29:04.033 --> 29:06.870
conspired to circumvent   
          an express order by       
          your commanding officer

29:06.911 --> 29:10.331
a whole year          
              before the cyclone    
              of 18 December.

29:10.373 --> 29:12.834
Now, please tell the court

29:12.876 --> 29:16.588
any other instances       
          of mistreatment           
          that occur to you.

29:18.214 --> 29:20.091
He cut off Internet access    
      for six months

29:20.133 --> 29:22.802
'cause he wasn't invited      
      to a screening by mistake.

29:22.844 --> 29:26.055
Uh, he restricted water use   
      in the middle of a heat wave

29:26.097 --> 29:29.267
'cause he said the men            
 were using too much,              
 they had to be taught a lesson.

29:29.309 --> 29:34.355
Did the captain ever issue        
 any rules or punishments          
 not permitted by regulations?

29:35.565 --> 29:38.109
He never did anything         
      not allowed by regulations.

29:38.151 --> 29:40.528
You don't like the captain,   
      do you, Lieutenant?

29:40.570 --> 29:42.489
Oh, I did.        
                  I did at first.

29:42.530 --> 29:44.240
Very much.                        
                          Mm-hmm.

29:44.282 --> 29:46.993
But I gradually       
              came to realize

29:47.035 --> 29:49.746
that he was a petty tyrant    
      and utterly incompetent.

29:49.788 --> 29:52.207
Did you think         
              he was insane, too?

29:52.248 --> 29:54.250
Not until the day     
              of the cyclone.

29:54.292 --> 29:57.045
Very well.                        
 Come to the day of the storm.

29:57.086 --> 29:58.922
Was your decision     
              to obey Maryk

29:58.963 --> 30:01.591
based on your judgment that   
      the captain had gone mad?

30:01.633 --> 30:04.803
Or was it based           
          on your hatred            
          of Captain Queeg?

30:06.429 --> 30:11.476
I-- I just-- I don't remember     
 my state of mind at that time.

30:12.143 --> 30:13.728
No further questions.

30:13.770 --> 30:16.898
Mr. Keith, you stated             
 you disliked Captain Queeg, yes?

30:16.940 --> 30:18.900
I did dislike him.

30:18.942 --> 30:21.653
And did you state all             
 your reasons for disliking him?   
              Not at all.

30:21.694 --> 30:24.239
Okay, well, please,               
 state the rest                    
 of those reasons now.

30:24.280 --> 30:27.242
Well, for one thing,          
      he extorted                   
      a thousand bucks from me.

30:27.283 --> 30:29.327
Objection.

30:29.369 --> 30:31.955
The issue in this case            
 is not whether Captain Queeg      
 was a model officer,

30:31.996 --> 30:33.832
but whether he was insane         
 on 18 December.

30:33.873 --> 30:35.959
Defense counsel hasn't            
 even touched that issue.

30:36.000 --> 30:38.503
Well, please the court,           
 this bears directly               
 on the fitness

30:38.545 --> 30:40.672
of Captain Queeg                  
 to command a naval vessel.

30:40.713 --> 30:43.049
And as evidence,                  
 it is nothing but clarification

30:43.091 --> 30:45.385
of Keith's dislike                
 for his commanding officer,

30:45.426 --> 30:49.347
a fact brought out                
 by trial counsel,                 
 at great pains, I might add,

30:49.389 --> 30:51.933
under direct examination.

30:53.393 --> 30:55.019
The objection is overruled.

30:56.563 --> 31:00.733
Mr. Keith,                        
 could you please describe         
 this so-called extortion?

31:00.775 --> 31:04.571
Well, this was back           
      last December                 
      in Port Doha, Qatar.

31:04.612 --> 31:07.740
Uh, the captain had this crate,

31:07.782 --> 31:11.035
this big crate                    
 full of duty-free whiskey         
 that he wanted to sneak aboard.

31:11.077 --> 31:12.871
He appointed me boat officer,

31:12.912 --> 31:15.665
and a working party started       
 to load the crate in the gig.

31:15.707 --> 31:17.876
It was incredibly heavy,

31:17.917 --> 31:22.505
and Captain Queeg...              
 got excited

31:22.547 --> 31:25.800
and started screaming out         
 a whole bunch                     
 of contradictory orders.

31:25.842 --> 31:28.136
Sailors got rattled,              
 they dropped the crate            
 in the water,

31:28.177 --> 31:31.556
it sank like a stone,             
 I was out a thousand bucks.

31:31.598 --> 31:33.641
No, you mean the captain      
      was out a thousand bucks.

31:33.683 --> 31:36.019
No, no, no, sir.                  
 I was.

31:36.060 --> 31:38.187
Captain informed me               
 it was my responsibility,

31:38.229 --> 31:40.398
'cause I was boat officer         
 in charge of loading,

31:40.440 --> 31:43.568
and he asked me                   
 what I wanted to do about it.

31:43.610 --> 31:45.236
I was supposed to go              
 on leave the next day.

31:45.278 --> 31:48.573
My girlfriend had flown out       
 from New York to be with me,

31:48.615 --> 31:50.366
so I went to the captain,

31:50.408 --> 31:53.578
I apologized for my stupidity,

31:53.620 --> 31:56.205
and I offered to pay              
 for the crate.

31:56.247 --> 31:59.709
He took my money                  
 and signed my leave papers.

32:00.960 --> 32:03.755
What other reasons do you have    
 for disliking Captain Queeg?

32:03.796 --> 32:05.465
Well, my chief reason             
 for disliking Captain Queeg

32:05.506 --> 32:07.759
was his cowardice                 
 in dangerous situations.

32:07.800 --> 32:08.760
Objection!

32:08.801 --> 32:10.011
Counsel                       
      is originating evidence

32:10.053 --> 32:12.305
beyond the scope              
      of direct examination.

32:12.347 --> 32:16.017
He is leading the witness     
      to irresponsible libel        
      of an officer of the Navy.

32:16.059 --> 32:18.895
Please the court,                 
 the witness's dislike             
 of Captain Queeg

32:18.937 --> 32:21.397
was not only in the scope         
 of direct examination,

32:21.439 --> 32:23.733
it was the key fact               
 brought out.

32:23.775 --> 32:27.779
Now, the witness has confessed    
 an ignorance of psychiatry.

32:28.571 --> 32:30.198
Things Captain Queeg did

32:30.239 --> 32:33.284
which forced the witness          
 in his ignorance                  
 to dislike him

32:33.326 --> 32:36.079
may in fact have been             
 the helpless acts                 
 of a sick man.

32:36.120 --> 32:39.207
I respectfully                
      urge my objection, sir.

32:39.248 --> 32:42.460
Let me remind everyone

32:42.502 --> 32:45.630
of the serious nature         
      of the issues                 
      in this line of questioning

32:45.672 --> 32:47.882
and the implications      
          involved.

32:48.841 --> 32:51.302
From the earliest days    
          of our service,

32:51.344 --> 32:54.806
the worst charge              
      that can be leveled against   
      a naval service officer,

32:54.847 --> 32:57.642
especially                    
      the commanding officer        
      of a vessel,

32:57.684 --> 33:02.647
is that he displays cowardice     
 or negligence in the face         
 of danger to his ship or crew.

33:03.815 --> 33:05.775
Counsel and the witness       
      are herewith cautioned

33:05.817 --> 33:09.821
that they are treading on     
      dangerous and unprecedented   
      grounds here.

33:11.030 --> 33:13.116
Court offers defense counsel 
      the opportunity

33:13.157 --> 33:15.451
to withdraw his question      
      from the record.

33:16.786 --> 33:19.205
My question stands, sir.

33:19.247 --> 33:21.290
Lieutenant Keith,

33:21.332 --> 33:24.711
you have the opportunity 
          to withdraw               
          or amend your answers.

33:24.752 --> 33:27.130
I stand by                
          what I said, sir.

33:27.880 --> 33:29.799
Very well.

33:29.841 --> 33:32.969
Court finds that the question     
 is within the scope               
 of direct examination

33:33.011 --> 33:35.930
and that the answer   
              is material.

33:35.972 --> 33:38.808
The objection         
              of the trial counsel 
              is overruled.

33:38.850 --> 33:41.019
Mr. Keith, can you describe       
 when and where

33:41.060 --> 33:44.188
the captain displayed             
 this aversion to danger?

33:44.230 --> 33:48.609
Uh, well,                         
 I guess the worst time            
 was a mine-sweeping operation

33:48.651 --> 33:50.194
in the Straits of Hormuz.

33:50.236 --> 33:52.196
That's where                      
 he got the nickname               
 Old Yellowstain.

33:52.238 --> 33:54.699
And this nickname,                
 Old Yellowstain,                  
 what does it imply?

33:54.741 --> 33:56.868
Well, cowardice, of course.

33:56.909 --> 33:59.662
It refers to a yellow dye marker 
 he dropped over the side.

33:59.704 --> 34:02.832
Describe. Describe            
      this Yellowstain incident     
      for us, please.

34:02.874 --> 34:04.876
I wasn't on                       
 the bridge at the time.

34:04.917 --> 34:07.003
I only heard                      
 about it afterwards--             
                  Oh! Objection.

34:07.045 --> 34:10.547
Does defense counsel              
 seriously expect to enter these   
 hearsay libels on the record?

34:10.590 --> 34:12.759
I withdraw the question,          
 okay?

34:12.800 --> 34:16.804
Defense will introduce            
 direct evidence                   
 on the Yellowstain incident.

34:16.846 --> 34:19.599
Strike the question           
      and the answer                
      from the record.

34:19.639 --> 34:21.809
Describe incidents                
 of cowardice

34:21.851 --> 34:24.228
to which you were                 
 an eyewitness,                    
 Mr. Keith.

34:25.146 --> 34:28.065
Any time there was        
          a difficult situation,

34:28.107 --> 34:31.319
Captain Queeg was always          
 to be found on the side           
 of the bridge away from it all.

34:31.360 --> 34:35.406
I saw that a dozen times          
 when I was officer of the day.    
 Thank you.

34:35.447 --> 34:37.574
No further questions.

34:37.617 --> 34:40.870
Mr. Keith,                        
 has Lieutenant Commander Queeg

34:40.911 --> 34:45.373
ever been investigated            
 or charged by higher authority

34:45.416 --> 34:49.420
for any of this alleged   
          unprofessional behavior   
          that you describe?

34:49.462 --> 34:50.838
No.

34:50.880 --> 34:53.091
Can you cite          
              any official records

34:53.132 --> 34:56.385
that'll substantiate      
          any of these fantastic

34:56.427 --> 34:58.596
and libelous stories      
          that you've been telling

34:58.638 --> 35:00.598
under the guidance    
              of defense counsel?

35:00.640 --> 35:02.308
Official records, no.

35:02.350 --> 35:04.852
Mr. Keith, do you     
              know for a fact

35:04.894 --> 35:08.231
that the crate that was lost 
      contained smuggled liquor?

35:08.272 --> 35:10.233
It's common knowledge.

35:10.274 --> 35:12.026
Common knowledge.

35:12.068 --> 35:14.570
Did you see the liquor    
          in the crate?             
                  No.

35:14.612 --> 35:18.658
Can you name one person           
 who will testify that they        
 saw liquor in the crate?

35:18.699 --> 35:21.702
Naturally, he was pretty 
          careful about that.       
 Okay, not one person.

35:21.744 --> 35:25.081
I just-- I don't--        
          I don't know who would    
          have actually seen it.

35:25.873 --> 35:27.166
Mr. Keith,            
              you've testified

35:27.208 --> 35:29.293
that you don't like       
          Captain Queeg.

35:29.335 --> 35:32.296
You're reporting as fact          
 every evil rumor about him

35:32.338 --> 35:35.967
and you're making                 
 wildly irresponsible charges      
 under oath.

35:36.008 --> 35:37.802
Isn't that the plain truth    
      of your testimony,            
      Mr. Keith?

35:37.844 --> 35:39.887
I haven't lied once.

35:39.929 --> 35:42.223
Mr. Keith, on the morning         
 that the captain was relieved,

35:42.265 --> 35:44.642
did you really think 
              he'd gone crazy?

35:45.601 --> 35:47.311
I said before,

35:47.353 --> 35:50.648
I can't say for sure          
      what my state of mind was,    
      or his.

35:51.691 --> 35:53.651
No more questions.

35:57.321 --> 35:58.990
Call Captain Southard.

36:04.287 --> 36:07.248
State your name, rank             
 and present station.

36:07.290 --> 36:08.833
Randolph Southard,

36:08.875 --> 36:12.128
Captain, US Navy      
              operations officer,   
              Fifth Fleet.

36:12.170 --> 36:13.838
You understand                    
 that you've been called           
 as an expert witness

36:13.880 --> 36:15.423
on Avenger-class                  
 ship handling?

36:15.464 --> 36:16.799
I do.

36:16.841 --> 36:18.217
State your qualifications.

36:18.259 --> 36:20.720
Some 20 years             
          on smaller combatants,

36:20.761 --> 36:22.430
ten years                 
          of commanding all types,

36:22.471 --> 36:25.433
including ships               
      ranging up to                 
      guided missile destroyers.

36:25.474 --> 36:29.103
To clarify for the members,       
 will you use the map              
 marked "Exhibit A"

36:29.145 --> 36:32.815
to illustrate                     
 the position of the   Caine         
 when she encountered the storm?

36:33.691 --> 36:37.570
The   Caine                     
      was approximately here.

36:37.612 --> 36:41.699
The storm hit         
              from the northeast,   
              heading southwest.

36:41.741 --> 36:43.743
Vessels of the task force     
      steered south

36:43.784 --> 36:45.620
in an attempt             
          to outrun the weather.

36:45.661 --> 36:48.664
The   Caine,   in her spot    
          on the right flank        
          of the sweep pattern,

36:48.706 --> 36:50.166
caught the worst of it.

36:50.208 --> 36:52.877
Rather than steering 
              with the wind aft,

36:52.919 --> 36:56.714
she turned north              
      into the wind and seized.

36:56.756 --> 37:00.635
That was the situation    
          in the strait             
          on the day in question.

37:00.676 --> 37:02.637
Thank you, Captain.           
      You may be seated.

37:02.678 --> 37:04.639
Trial counsel,                
      you may proceed.

37:04.680 --> 37:06.140
Thank you.

37:07.308 --> 37:10.895
Captain, let's say that, 
          hypothetically,

37:10.937 --> 37:13.481
you're the one        
              who's in command      
              of the vessel.

37:13.522 --> 37:16.108
A cyclone blows up    
              without warning       
              traveling west

37:16.150 --> 37:18.236
and you're directly   
              in the path of it.

37:18.277 --> 37:19.987
The wind keeps increasing,

37:20.029 --> 37:22.531
its direction                     
 holding steady from the north.

37:22.573 --> 37:26.786
Soon your wind                    
 is force ten to 12                
 and your seas are mountainous.

37:26.827 --> 37:29.455
Under the circumstances, 
          what would you do?

37:29.497 --> 37:31.832
Well, I'd execute                 
 the classic Navy maneuver

37:31.874 --> 37:34.210
known as getting                  
 the hell out of there.

37:34.252 --> 37:36.087
And how would you go 
              about that, Captain?

37:36.128 --> 37:38.256
Well, it's almost                 
 rule of thumb.

37:38.297 --> 37:40.424
You say the winds                 
 from the north are 90 knots,

37:40.466 --> 37:43.594
center of the cyclone             
 coming at you from the west.

37:43.636 --> 37:45.429
The best course is south.

37:45.471 --> 37:48.349
You might have to head            
 a couple of points                
 one way or the other,

37:48.391 --> 37:49.934
depending on your seas,

37:49.976 --> 37:53.854
but there's only one way          
 out of that mess-- south.

37:53.896 --> 37:57.108
But then you have                 
 a terribly strong stern wind,     
 don't you?

37:57.149 --> 37:58.943
What about it?

37:58.985 --> 38:02.488
Well, can a small vessel      
      ride safely going downwind    
      in such conditions?

38:02.530 --> 38:06.284
She'll ride just as well      
      going downwind as upwind.

38:06.325 --> 38:08.744
In fact,                      
      with your high freeboard      
      going forward,

38:08.786 --> 38:10.663
a smaller vessel              
      tends to back in the wind.

38:10.705 --> 38:15.751
Other things being equal,         
 she'll do slightly                
 better going downwind.

38:15.793 --> 38:18.963
How about turning north       
      in those circumstances        
      and heading into the wind?

38:19.005 --> 38:24.468
Well, that would be               
 dubious and dangerous,            
 not to mention idiotic.

38:24.510 --> 38:26.595
Why, sir?

38:26.637 --> 38:29.598
Well, you're heading yourself     
 right back into the path          
 of the cyclone.

38:29.640 --> 38:33.227
Unless you're interested      
      in sinking,                   
      that's not smart.

38:33.269 --> 38:34.979
That's all, sir.

38:35.021 --> 38:39.775
Captain, have you ever        
      conned a ship                 
      at the center of a cyclone?

38:39.817 --> 38:41.694
Negative.

38:41.736 --> 38:45.114
Been on the fringes often,    
      but always managed            
      to avoid the center.

38:45.156 --> 38:49.035
And have you ever commanded   
      a mine countermeasures ship? 
      Negative.

38:49.076 --> 38:52.455
Okay, this trial, sir,            
 concerns an Avenger-class MCM

38:52.496 --> 38:54.874
at the center of                  
 a very dangerous storm.

38:54.915 --> 38:56.834
I'm aware of that.

38:56.876 --> 39:00.338
I've had MCMs under my command,   
 and I've read the book on them.

39:00.379 --> 39:02.465
They don't differ             
      from smaller-class vessels

39:02.506 --> 39:06.927
in terms of characteristics       
 and handling in rough weather.

39:06.969 --> 39:09.138
I only ask these questions,       
 sir,

39:09.180 --> 39:11.640
because you are                   
 the only expert                   
 ship-handling witness,

39:11.682 --> 39:15.186
and I believe the extent          
 of your expert knowledge          
 should be clear to the court.

39:15.227 --> 39:17.271
Well,                     
          I've handled these ships

39:17.313 --> 39:20.775
in almost                     
      every conceivable situation   
      for the last ten years.

39:20.816 --> 39:23.944
Haven't handled               
      a mine countermeasures        
      at the center of a cyclone,

39:23.986 --> 39:27.114
but I don't know              
      who the hell has besides      
      the skipper of the   Caine.

39:27.156 --> 39:29.200
That's                            
 a thousand-to-one shot.

39:29.241 --> 39:32.328
Then would you state,         
      without reservation,

39:32.370 --> 39:36.374
that the same rules hold          
 for an MCM                        
 at the center of a cyclone?

39:36.415 --> 39:40.544
At the center of a cyclone,       
 there are no hard                 
 and fast rules.

39:40.586 --> 39:43.297
That's one situation              
 where it's all up                 
 to the commanding officer.

39:43.339 --> 39:45.508
Too many things                   
 happen too fast.

39:45.549 --> 39:47.510
Mmm.

39:47.551 --> 39:50.721
You remember                      
 the hypothetical question         
 put to you by trial counsel

39:50.763 --> 39:52.515
about the storm, yes?

39:52.556 --> 39:53.849
I do.

39:53.891 --> 39:55.976
I want you to assume 
              in that situation

39:56.018 --> 39:58.687
that the wind and the seas    
      become bigger.

39:58.729 --> 40:02.233
They become bigger            
      than anything-- anything      
      you have ever experienced.

40:02.274 --> 40:03.943
You have lost control     
          of your ship, sir.

40:03.984 --> 40:06.237
You actually believe              
 she could sink.

40:06.278 --> 40:08.906
You are in                
          the worst-case scenario.

40:08.948 --> 40:12.368
Do you bring around north     
      into the wind,

40:12.410 --> 40:15.913
or do you continue south,     
      stern to the wind?

40:15.955 --> 40:17.748
You're getting    
                  very extreme.

40:17.790 --> 40:20.000
Yes, sir, I am.           
          Would you prefer not      
          to answer the question?

40:20.042 --> 40:22.044
I'll answer it.   
 Please.

40:22.086 --> 40:24.255
In the worst-case scenario,

40:24.296 --> 40:27.591
I'd come around the north,    
      into the wind, if I could.

40:27.633 --> 40:31.053
But only                      
      in the worst-case scenario.   
              Why?

40:31.095 --> 40:34.056
Because the engines           
      in your rudder have           
      the best chance that way.

40:34.098 --> 40:38.519
That's why.                       
 It's your last chance             
 to keep control of your ship.

40:38.561 --> 40:42.273
But aren't you heading back       
 into the center of the storm?     
 First things first.

40:42.314 --> 40:43.983
If you're on                  
      the verge of sinking,

40:44.024 --> 40:46.068
you about as bad off          
      as you can get.

40:46.110 --> 40:47.653
Mind you, you said            
      worst-case scenario.

40:47.695 --> 40:52.324
I did, sir.                       
 Thank you very much.              
 No further questions.

40:52.366 --> 40:54.660
Captain,                  
          who, in your opinion,     
          is the best judge

40:54.702 --> 40:57.580
as to whether a ship is in        
 the worst-case scenario?

40:57.621 --> 41:01.292
There's only one judge.           
 The commanding officer.

41:01.333 --> 41:03.169
Why, sir?

41:03.210 --> 41:06.505
The Navy made him captain         
 'cause his knowledge              
 of the sea and of ships

41:06.547 --> 41:09.383
is better than anyone else's      
 on the ship.

41:09.425 --> 41:14.138
It's very common                  
 for some subordinate officers     
 to think the ship is sinking

41:14.180 --> 41:17.224
when all that's happening         
 is a little weather.

41:17.266 --> 41:20.060
Well, don't you think, sir,       
 that when his subordinates

41:20.102 --> 41:22.062
all agree that the ship           
 is going down

41:22.104 --> 41:23.814
that the captain ought            
 to listen to them?

41:23.856 --> 41:25.816
Negative.

41:25.858 --> 41:29.153
Panic is a common hazard 
          at sea.

41:29.195 --> 41:31.322
The highest function of command   
 is to override

41:31.363 --> 41:34.575
and listen to nothing     
          but the voice of his own 
          professional judgment.

41:35.868 --> 41:38.162
Call Dr. Joan Lundeen.

41:43.042 --> 41:45.169
State your name, rank     
          and present station.

41:45.211 --> 41:47.338
Lieutenant Commander              
 Joan Lundeen,

41:47.379 --> 41:49.965
Medical Corps, US Navy,           
 Head of Psychiatry,

41:50.007 --> 41:52.176
US Naval Hospital,            
      San Francisco.

41:52.218 --> 41:55.179
Were you the head of              
 the medical board that examined   
 Lieutenant Commander Queeg?

41:55.221 --> 41:56.555
I was.

41:56.597 --> 41:59.975
And how long                      
 did your examination last,        
 Doctor?

42:00.017 --> 42:03.687
We had the commander              
 under constant observation        
 and testing for three weeks.

42:03.729 --> 42:05.773
[Challee]                         
 And what was the finding          
 of the board?

42:05.814 --> 42:08.817
Commander Queeg was discharged    
 with a clean bill of health.

42:08.859 --> 42:13.572
Doctor, is it possible        
      that two months ago,          
      on December 18th,

42:13.614 --> 42:16.367
he was in such a state    
          of psychotic collapse

42:16.408 --> 42:19.495
that relieving him    
              from naval command    
              would be justified?

42:19.537 --> 42:20.788
No.

42:20.829 --> 42:22.665
Is it possible    
                  for a sane man

42:22.706 --> 42:26.627
to perform offensive,     
          disagreeable,             
          foolish acts?

42:26.669 --> 42:28.379
It happens every day.

42:28.420 --> 42:31.006
We didn't find                
      that the commander            
      was a perfect officer.

42:31.048 --> 42:34.718
Yet, you still say        
          that to relieve him       
          from naval command

42:34.760 --> 42:37.888
because of mental illness     
      would be unjustified?

42:37.930 --> 42:41.058
Completely unjustified.

42:41.725 --> 42:43.269
Thank you.

42:43.769 --> 42:45.980
Dr. Lundeen,

42:46.021 --> 42:48.023
my background is legal,       
      not medical,

42:48.065 --> 42:51.569
so I hope you'll bear with me     
 as I try to clarify               
 some technical terms.

42:51.610 --> 42:53.320
Of course.

42:53.362 --> 42:57.366
I'm going to ask some             
 pretty elementary questions.      
                      All right.

42:57.408 --> 43:00.077
Would you say Commander Queeg     
 is absolutely normal?

43:00.119 --> 43:01.912
[chuckles]

43:01.954 --> 43:05.291
Well, normality, you know,    
      is a fiction in psychiatry.   
 Mmm.

43:05.332 --> 43:08.669
No adult is without problems 
      except a happy imbecile.

43:08.711 --> 43:10.838
What are                      
      Commander Queeg's problems?

43:10.879 --> 43:14.508
You might say his             
      overall problem is one of     
      an inferiority complex

43:14.550 --> 43:16.635
generated                     
      by an unhappy childhood

43:16.677 --> 43:19.972
and aggravated                    
 by certain adult experiences.

43:20.014 --> 43:22.308
Unhappy childhood                 
 in what way?

43:22.349 --> 43:26.562
Divorced parents,         
          financial trouble,

43:26.604 --> 43:28.105
problems at school.

43:28.147 --> 43:30.482
And the aggravating factors   
      in adult life?

43:31.775 --> 43:33.235
In his adult life,

43:33.277 --> 43:35.529
the commander is troubled         
 by his low standing

43:35.571 --> 43:37.906
in his academy class              
 and other such factors,

43:37.948 --> 43:39.783
but he has                        
 become well-adjusted.

43:39.825 --> 43:42.911
Mmm. Can you describe             
 the nature of that adjustment?

43:42.953 --> 43:46.457
His identity as a naval officer   
 is the essential factor.

43:46.498 --> 43:48.917
It's the key                      
 to his personal security.

43:48.959 --> 43:52.463
Therefore,                        
 he has a fixed anxiety            
 about protecting his standing.

43:52.504 --> 43:54.465
That would account            
      for his harshness.

43:54.506 --> 43:56.592
Would he be slow                  
 to admit mistakes?

43:56.634 --> 43:59.303
Yes, of course.               
      There's nothing               
      unbalanced in that.

43:59.345 --> 44:02.514
Oh, really? I mean,           
      would he be a perfectionist?

44:02.556 --> 44:04.600
Such a personality        
          would be.

44:04.642 --> 44:06.310
Inclined to hound     
              his subordinates

44:06.352 --> 44:07.895
over the smallest         
          little details.

44:07.936 --> 44:11.440
Any mistake           
              of a subordinate      
              is intolerable

44:11.482 --> 44:13.525
because it might cause him harm.

44:13.567 --> 44:17.529
Yet he will not admit mistakes    
 that he makes himself.

44:17.571 --> 44:21.742
You might say             
          that he revises reality   
          in his own mind

44:21.784 --> 44:23.661
so he comes out blameless.

44:23.702 --> 44:27.456
Doctor, isn't                 
      distortion of reality         
      a symptom of mental illness?

44:27.498 --> 44:30.250
It's a question of degree.

44:30.292 --> 44:32.628
Each one of us        
              has our own reality.

44:32.670 --> 44:37.007
Yes, Doctor, but doesn't          
 Commander Queeg distort reality   
 more, say, than you do?

44:37.049 --> 44:39.301
Yes, that's his weakness.

44:39.343 --> 44:41.261
Other people              
          have other weaknesses.

44:41.303 --> 44:43.430
It's definitely           
          not disabling.

44:43.472 --> 44:48.519
Well, if he's criticized,     
      would he think he was         
      being unjustly persecuted?

44:49.353 --> 44:51.271
It's all one pattern,

44:51.313 --> 44:55.109
all stemming                      
 from one basic premise            
 that he must try to be perfect.

44:55.150 --> 44:56.819
Inclined to stubbornness, then.

44:56.860 --> 45:00.322
Well, you'll have             
      a certain rigidity            
      of personality

45:00.364 --> 45:02.366
in such an individual.

45:02.408 --> 45:04.702
His inner insecurity          
      stops him from admitting

45:04.743 --> 45:07.663
that those who differ         
      from him may be right.

45:07.705 --> 45:12.960
Doctor, you just testified that   
 the following symptoms exist      
 in Commander Queeg's behavior.

45:13.001 --> 45:14.670
We have rigidity                  
 of personality.

45:14.712 --> 45:16.422
We have feelings                  
 of persecution.

45:16.463 --> 45:18.507
We have                           
 unreasonable suspicion.

45:18.549 --> 45:20.217
We have withdrawal                
 from reality.

45:20.259 --> 45:22.261
We have performance anxiety.

45:22.302 --> 45:24.805
We have an unreal basic premise

45:24.847 --> 45:27.683
and an obsessive sense            
 of self-righteousness.

45:27.725 --> 45:31.061
All mild, sir.                
      All well-compensated.

45:31.103 --> 45:33.105
Yes, Doctor, yes.

45:33.147 --> 45:37.276
But is there                      
 an inclusive psychiatric term,    
 one label for this syndrome?

45:37.317 --> 45:40.154
Syndrome? Who said anything       
 about a syndrome?

45:40.195 --> 45:44.700
You're misusing a term.           
 There's no syndrome               
 because there's no disease.

45:44.742 --> 45:46.660
I'll rephrase it.

45:46.702 --> 45:48.871
Do these symptoms     
              fall into

45:48.912 --> 45:53.000
a single pattern              
      of neurotic disturbance,      
      a common psychiatric class?

45:53.041 --> 45:55.544
I know                    
          what you're getting at.   
 Well?

45:55.586 --> 45:59.840
It's a paranoid personality,      
 but that is not                   
 a disabling affliction.

45:59.882 --> 46:02.092
Doctor--                          
 A what personality,               
 Doctor?

46:02.134 --> 46:04.011
Paranoid.

46:04.052 --> 46:07.181
A paranoid?       
              Yes, paranoid.

46:09.725 --> 46:12.728
Um, Doctor, in a--

46:14.480 --> 46:17.941
in a paranoid personality,    
      like Commander Queeg's,

46:17.983 --> 46:19.860
would he-- I'm--

46:19.902 --> 46:22.070
I'm gonna put this to you     
      hypothetically.

46:22.112 --> 46:24.573
Can a man have                    
 a paranoid personality

46:24.615 --> 46:27.159
that would not disable him    
      for subordinate duties,

46:27.201 --> 46:28.786
but would disable him     
          for command?

46:28.827 --> 46:30.954
It's conceivable.

46:30.996 --> 46:34.166
And is the disabling factor   
      likely to be detected         
      in a personal interview?

46:34.208 --> 46:36.210
With a skilled        
              psychiatrist, yes.

46:36.251 --> 46:38.962
Why? I mean,                      
 why is a psychiatrist needed?

46:39.004 --> 46:41.965
Can't an educated, intelligent    
 person detect a paranoid?

46:42.007 --> 46:44.885
Well, you evidently           
      aren't too well acquainted    
      with the pattern.

46:44.927 --> 46:47.346
The distinguishing mark   
          of this neurosis

46:47.387 --> 46:51.809
is the extreme plausibility   
      and a most convincing normal 
      manner on the surface,

46:51.850 --> 46:54.311
particularly              
          in self-justification.

46:54.353 --> 46:56.271
Self-justification.

46:56.313 --> 46:57.981
Thank you, Doctor.

46:59.107 --> 47:00.484
No further questions.

47:00.526 --> 47:02.820
[officer] The court wishes    
      to clear up one point.

47:02.861 --> 47:07.574
Doctor, is...                     
 is such a thing possible--

47:07.616 --> 47:10.285
Well, let me put it this way.

47:10.327 --> 47:12.162
Let's say that a man              
 with a mild condition

47:12.204 --> 47:16.083
is not disabled for all           
 the usual stresses of command.

47:16.124 --> 47:20.838
Now let's say those stresses      
 are multiplied manifold           
 by an extreme emergency.

47:20.879 --> 47:23.799
Would there then be a tendency    
 to make erroneous judgments?

47:23.841 --> 47:25.551
There might be, sir.

47:25.592 --> 47:28.720
Of course, extreme stress         
 does that to almost anybody.

47:28.762 --> 47:30.722
It's not supposed to do it        
 to commanding officers.

47:30.764 --> 47:34.977
No, but practically speaking,     
 sir, they're human.

47:38.564 --> 47:41.149
State your name, rank     
          and present station.

47:41.191 --> 47:43.902
Allen Bird, MD,                   
 US Navy Reserve.

47:43.944 --> 47:46.905
I was called to serve on          
 the psychiatric evaluation team.

47:46.947 --> 47:49.408
Was this the board that       
      was headed by Dr. Lundeen

47:49.449 --> 47:52.744
which recently inquired into 
      the mental health of          
      Lieutenant Commander Queeg?

47:52.786 --> 47:54.955
Yes.                  
 And what was the finding          
 of the board?

47:54.997 --> 47:58.125
We found that the commander   
      is mentally fit               
      for command now

47:58.166 --> 48:00.544
and has never been unfit.

48:00.586 --> 48:03.380
Did you find any indication       
 that Commander Queeg

48:03.422 --> 48:06.717
had what is known             
      as a paranoid personality?

48:06.758 --> 48:10.846
Well, I prefer to call it         
 obsessive personality             
 with paranoid features.

48:10.888 --> 48:14.933
Right, but this did not       
      indicate mental unfitness.    
          No.

48:14.975 --> 48:18.186
You agree, Doctor,    
              that Commander Queeg 
              is mentally fit now

48:18.228 --> 48:20.981
and must have been    
              mentally fit          
              on December 18th

48:21.023 --> 48:23.275
when he was relieved 
              on the grounds        
              of mental illness?

48:23.317 --> 48:25.360
That was                          
 our unanimous conclusion.

48:25.402 --> 48:27.404
Thank you, Doctor.

48:27.446 --> 48:29.239
[Greenwald]                       
 Dr. Bird,

48:29.281 --> 48:32.492
do you have any special training 
 in psychoanalysis?

48:32.534 --> 48:34.369
Yes.

48:34.411 --> 48:37.164
Okay, and in psychoanalysis, 
      is there such a thing         
      as mental illness?

48:37.205 --> 48:39.917
There are disturbed people        
 and adjusted people.

48:39.958 --> 48:41.919
But those terms,              
      "disturbed" and "adjusted,"

48:41.960 --> 48:44.421
they correspond roughly   
          in layman's terms

48:44.463 --> 48:46.506
to "sick" and "well,"     
          as we use them.

48:46.548 --> 48:48.592
Very roughly, yes.

48:48.634 --> 48:53.472
Would you say                 
      Commander Queeg suffers       
      from an inferiority complex?

48:53.513 --> 48:57.225
Yes, but it's...              
      well-compensated.

48:57.267 --> 48:59.937
Is there a difference     
          between "compensated"     
          and "adjusted"?

48:59.978 --> 49:01.146
Most definitely.

49:01.188 --> 49:03.774
Okay, could you please            
 describe that for us?

49:03.815 --> 49:06.193
Well, let's say               
      a man is suffering

49:06.234 --> 49:09.863
from some deep-seated         
      psychological disturbance.

49:09.905 --> 49:13.951
He can compensate             
      by finding outlets            
      for his peculiar drives.

49:13.992 --> 49:19.164
Okay. So, has Commander Queeg     
 ever been psychoanalyzed?

49:19.206 --> 49:21.833
No.   
 He's in your terms, then,         
 a disturbed person?

49:21.875 --> 49:24.711
Yes, he is.                   
      Not disabled, however,        
      by the disturbance.

49:24.753 --> 49:26.964
Okay, how is he compensated?

49:28.215 --> 49:29.925
Mainly two ways.

49:29.967 --> 49:33.053
The paranoid pattern,             
 which is useless                  
 and not desirable,

49:33.095 --> 49:36.765
and his naval career,             
 which is extremely useful         
 and desirable.

49:36.807 --> 49:39.643
Yes, Doctor, have you         
      noticed that little thing     
      he does with his hands?

49:39.685 --> 49:41.395
You mean                          
 rolling the steel balls?          
              Yes.

49:41.436 --> 49:43.230
Could you describe    
              that for us, please?

49:43.271 --> 49:45.816
It's an incessant rolling         
 of two marbles in his hand.

49:45.857 --> 49:48.568
Mm-hmm.               
              Why does he do it?

49:48.610 --> 49:51.279
Oh, uh, his hands tremble.

49:51.321 --> 49:54.199
He does it to still his hands     
 and conceal the trembling.

49:54.241 --> 49:55.492
Why do his hands tremble?

49:55.534 --> 49:58.704
Inner tension.                    
 It's a surface symptom.

49:58.745 --> 50:01.206
Doctor, you've testified 
          that Commander Queeg

50:01.248 --> 50:03.917
is a disturbed,               
      not an adjusted person, yes?

50:03.959 --> 50:06.336
Yes.                              
          So he is,                 
          in layman's terms, sick.

50:06.378 --> 50:08.672
Yes?

50:08.714 --> 50:12.134
I remember agreeing to the        
 rough resemblance of the terms    
 "disturbed" and "sick,"

50:12.175 --> 50:14.594
but by those terms                
 an awful lot of people            
 are sick.

50:14.636 --> 50:17.639
Yes, Doctor, but this court   
      only has Commander Queeg's    
      sickness at issue.

50:17.681 --> 50:21.435
If he is sick, how could      
      your board have given him     
      a clean bill of health?

50:21.476 --> 50:24.938
Y-You're playing on words.        
 We found no disability.

50:24.980 --> 50:27.357
Doctor, just suppose      
          for an instant

50:27.399 --> 50:30.986
that the requirements of command 
 are way more severe               
 than you believe them to be.

50:31.028 --> 50:34.197
Wouldn't even this mild sickness 
 be enough to disable him?

50:34.239 --> 50:36.658
That's absurdly hypothetical,     
 because--                         
 Oh, is it?

50:36.700 --> 50:38.827
Have you ever had         
          sea duty, Doctor?         
 No.

50:38.869 --> 50:41.872
No? How long have you been    
      in the service of the Navy?

50:41.913 --> 50:43.206
Five months. 
          Five months?

50:43.248 --> 50:45.876
Five--            
                  Six months.       
          Six, I guess now.

50:45.917 --> 50:47.919
Six months in the service         
 of the Navy.

50:47.961 --> 50:51.381
Have you ever had any dealings    
 with ships' captains              
 prior to this case?

50:51.423 --> 50:52.549
No.                   
                              No?

50:52.591 --> 50:54.009
Then on what do you base

50:54.051 --> 50:55.427
your estimate                     
 of the requirements of command?

50:55.469 --> 50:57.387
My general knowledge.

50:57.429 --> 51:00.390
Would you say it takes somebody, 
 a person of exceptional ability,

51:00.432 --> 51:03.310
highly gifted, highly skilled     
 to be a commander                 
 of a naval vessel?

51:03.351 --> 51:04.728
No.                   
 No. Really?

51:04.770 --> 51:07.147
Not highly gifted, no.        
 Then what?

51:07.189 --> 51:09.691
Uh, reasonable responses.     
 "Reasonable"?

51:09.733 --> 51:11.777
Uh, fairly good               
      intelligence.                 
 "Fairly good"?

51:11.818 --> 51:14.196
Sufficient training           
      and experience, but--

51:14.237 --> 51:17.199
Is this enough equipment,     
      say, for a highly skilled     
      psychiatrist?

51:17.240 --> 51:19.076
Not exactly.

51:19.117 --> 51:21.328
So in other words,        
          it takes more ability     
          to be a psychiatrist

51:21.369 --> 51:23.997
than it does to be    
              the commander of      
              a US naval vessel.

51:24.039 --> 51:26.666
It takes-- That is,           
      uh, different abilities       
      are required.

51:26.708 --> 51:28.919
You're making the comparison,     
 not I.

51:28.960 --> 51:31.713
No, Doctor, you're the one        
 that said you don't think         
 Commander Queeg's sickness

51:31.755 --> 51:34.049
should disable him for command.

51:34.091 --> 51:37.552
I am suggesting that since        
 you evidently know little about   
 the requirements of command,

51:37.594 --> 51:39.429
that you may be wrong         
      in your conclusion.

51:39.471 --> 51:41.932
Well, I reject                
      your suggestion.              
                  Oh, you do? Why?

51:41.973 --> 51:44.226
Because you've deliberately       
 substituted the word "sick,"

51:44.267 --> 51:46.853
which is a loose--                
 a polarizing--                    
                          Have I?

51:46.895 --> 51:48.605
A what word, Doctor?          
                      Polarizing.

51:48.647 --> 51:50.440
A polarizing word.            
              I never said "sick."

51:50.482 --> 51:53.276
My grasp of the requirements      
 of command is adequate,

51:53.318 --> 51:56.071
or I would have                   
 disqualified myself               
 from serving on the board.

51:56.113 --> 51:57.781
Maybe you should                  
 have disqualified yourself.

51:57.823 --> 51:59.491
Objection!                        
 The witness is being badgered!

51:59.533 --> 52:01.618
I withdraw                
          my last statement.

52:01.660 --> 52:03.537
No further questions.

52:03.578 --> 52:06.206
Doctor, the defense counsel   
      has managed to put            
      words into your mouth

52:06.248 --> 52:08.542
that I'm certain 
                  you don't mean.

52:08.583 --> 52:11.419
I'm not aware that                
 he succeeded in putting           
 any words into my mouth.

52:11.461 --> 52:14.464
Doctor, he drew               
      the implication from you      
      that Captain Queeg is sick.

52:14.506 --> 52:17.634
Surely you don't--    
 I'm careful in my use             
 of terminology.

52:17.676 --> 52:20.846
I did not use the term "sick."

52:20.887 --> 52:25.684
Captain Queeg is definitely       
 not disabled for command,         
 which is the only issue here.

52:28.770 --> 52:30.313
Prosecution rests.

52:32.023 --> 52:33.650
Defense,              
              present your case.

52:34.860 --> 52:36.653
I call the accused.

52:38.029 --> 52:41.741
Does the accused request that     
 he be permitted to testify?       
                      Yes, sir.

52:41.783 --> 52:43.785
You have the right        
          not to take the stand.

52:43.827 --> 52:46.663
If you don't take the stand, 
      that fact won't be            
      to your prejudice.

52:46.705 --> 52:50.333
If you take the stand,            
 you may be subjected to           
 a rigorous cross-examination.

52:50.375 --> 52:52.252
I understand that,    
              sir.

52:52.294 --> 52:54.212
You may take the stand.

52:57.382 --> 52:59.885
State your name, rank             
 and present position.

52:59.926 --> 53:01.303
Steven Maryk,             
          Lieutenant, US Navy,

53:01.344 --> 53:03.180
executive officer         
          of the USS   Caine.

53:03.221 --> 53:05.724
Are you the accused               
 in this court-martial?            
              Yes, I am.

53:05.765 --> 53:08.143
What was your occupation          
 in civilian life?

53:08.185 --> 53:10.937
Helping my father         
          in his fishing business. 
          We own a couple boats.

53:10.979 --> 53:12.898
Where?                            
              San Francisco.

53:12.939 --> 53:15.317
Then you were familiar            
 with the problems                 
 of ocean-going ship handling

53:15.358 --> 53:17.152
prior to joining the Navy?

53:17.194 --> 53:19.654
Yes, I've been on boats       
      since I was 14.

53:19.696 --> 53:23.325
Did you relieve                   
 the commander of the USS   Caine    
 18th December, 2022?

53:23.366 --> 53:25.410
Yes, I did.

53:25.452 --> 53:27.996
Was the   Caine   in trouble          
 when you relieved its captain?    
                      Yes, it was.

53:28.038 --> 53:31.541
And on what facts                 
 do you base that judgment?        
          Well, several things.

53:31.583 --> 53:33.168
We couldn't hold course.

53:33.210 --> 53:35.545
We broached three times   
          in an hour.               
 "Broached"?

53:35.587 --> 53:39.174
Yes, wind and sea took charge     
 and tossed us sideways            
 ten minutes at a time.

53:39.216 --> 53:42.052
We were rolling too steeply       
 for the inclinometer to record.

53:42.093 --> 53:45.388
We were shipping water            
 out of the wheelhouse.            
 The generators were cutting out.

53:45.430 --> 53:48.016
The ship was not responding   
      to emergency rudder           
      and engine settings.

53:48.058 --> 53:49.517
We were lost              
          and out of control.

53:49.559 --> 53:51.645
And did you inform                
 your captain of this?             
                      Yes.

53:51.686 --> 53:55.732
Repeatedly for an hour.       
      I begged him                  
      to come north into the wind.

53:55.774 --> 53:57.234
What was his reply?

53:57.275 --> 54:00.737
Well, mostly          
              just a glazed look    
              and no answer.

54:01.655 --> 54:03.490
Mr. Maryk,

54:03.531 --> 54:07.327
when did you start                
 keeping your medical log          
 on Commander Queeg?

54:07.369 --> 54:09.704
Shortly after the incident    
      with the mines                
      in the Straits of Hormuz.

54:09.746 --> 54:13.500
And why did you start it?         
      I began to think the captain 
      might be mentally ill.

54:13.541 --> 54:16.127
Why?                              
          Because of the yellow     
          dye marker business.

54:16.169 --> 54:19.839
You mean the incident             
 where the commander acquired      
 the nickname Old Yellowstain?

54:19.881 --> 54:21.091
Yes.

54:21.132 --> 54:23.468
Were you an eyewitness            
 to this occurrence?

54:23.510 --> 54:25.428
I was navigator.      
              I was right there     
              on the bridge.

54:25.470 --> 54:28.056
Please describe                   
 this Yellowstain incident.

54:29.391 --> 54:32.352
It was the third day 
              of an assigned sweep 
              with two other MCMs.

54:32.394 --> 54:33.895
Mm-hmm.

54:33.937 --> 54:36.731
We had detected               
      a field of acoustic mines.

54:36.773 --> 54:38.733
[speaking louder]             
      It was the third day

54:38.775 --> 54:40.777
of an assigned sweep          
      with two other MCMs.

54:40.819 --> 54:42.779
We detected a field               
 of acoustic mines

54:42.821 --> 54:44.781
in the narrowest part             
 of the strait

54:44.823 --> 54:46.950
and we'd been ordered             
 to destroy them in place          
 using high explosives.

54:46.992 --> 54:50.287
And that's delicate business.     
 It's gotta be done just right.

54:50.328 --> 54:52.956
We milled around out there    
      for a while.

54:52.998 --> 54:56.042
Then the captain decided 
          not to set the charges.

54:56.084 --> 54:58.086
He gave us some excuse    
          about faulty equipment.

54:58.128 --> 55:00.797
I checked the gear.               
 It was in perfect working order.

55:00.839 --> 55:02.716
And the captain       
              wouldn't hear it.

55:02.757 --> 55:05.260
He said the tech was incompetent 
 and he knew better.

55:05.302 --> 55:08.054
So we dropped         
              a yellow dye marker   
              over the side,

55:08.096 --> 55:10.223
radioed to the other MCM 
          to destroy the mines.

55:10.265 --> 55:14.102
They radioed back                 
 to slow down, but we just--       
 we steamed right out of there.

55:14.144 --> 55:15.478
[Greenwald] "Steamed."            
 Now, Mr. Maryk--

55:15.520 --> 55:18.023
The court wishes to       
          question the witness.

55:18.064 --> 55:21.776
Lieutenant, you say               
 the gear was in working order.    
 Did you check it personally?

55:21.818 --> 55:24.362
Yes, sir, along with              
 the chief electronic tech         
 and the sonar men.

55:24.404 --> 55:26.406
It was fine.                      
 There was absolutely              
 nothing wrong with the gear.

55:26.448 --> 55:29.075
And after you steamed away,   
      was there any danger          
      due to shock waves

55:29.117 --> 55:30.702
from the underwater   
              detonations?

55:30.744 --> 55:32.829
No.                               
 No, there was not.

55:32.871 --> 55:35.498
MCMs are designed to              
 withstand that kind of thing.     
 We do this all the time.

55:35.540 --> 55:39.252
Now, you say these boats 
          signaled to you           
          to slow down.

55:39.294 --> 55:41.921
Yes, sir.                         
          Was the signal reported   
          to your captain?

55:41.963 --> 55:43.673
I reported it to him myself.

55:43.715 --> 55:45.467
Was he aware that     
              he was steaming away

55:45.508 --> 55:47.927
from his assigned spot    
          in the sweep formation?

55:47.969 --> 55:50.513
It was obvious to                 
 everyone on the bridge.           
 I pointed it out.

55:50.555 --> 55:52.682
I said we were breaking           
 the sweep pattern,

55:52.724 --> 55:54.976
that the other vessels            
 would not know                    
 where we'd found the mines.

55:55.018 --> 55:59.439
And that is when he said,         
 "We'll drop a yellow dye marker   
 over the side then."

55:59.481 --> 56:01.358
You may continue.

56:01.399 --> 56:04.736
Mr. Maryk, why didn't             
 you go immediately                
 to a higher authority

56:04.778 --> 56:07.447
with your doubts                  
 about Captain Queeg's             
 mental health?

56:07.489 --> 56:10.325
I felt if I had a record,     
      I'd be on stronger ground.

56:10.367 --> 56:12.410
That's when I decided         
      to keep the medical log.

56:12.452 --> 56:15.872
If I was wrong,                   
 I'd just burn it.                 
 I kept it under lock and key.

56:15.914 --> 56:17.791
And what,                         
 in your opinion,

56:17.832 --> 56:20.460
made an incident worthy           
 of keeping a record               
 in the medical log?

56:20.502 --> 56:22.670
Any act that seemed           
      abnormal or strange.

56:22.712 --> 56:24.714
Like what?                        
      Like the coffee machine.

56:24.756 --> 56:26.299
The coffee machine                
 business?                         
              Yes.

56:26.341 --> 56:28.134
Well, please describe             
 the coffee machine thing.

56:28.176 --> 56:30.053
We had a new coffee machine   
      in the wardroom.

56:30.095 --> 56:33.765
And, uh, Captain              
      really liked his coffee.      
      But you had to be careful.

56:33.807 --> 56:36.309
You couldn't leave it             
 plugged in too long               
 or the thing would burn out.

56:36.351 --> 56:38.520
That's exactly what happened.

56:38.561 --> 56:40.814
One of the guys assigned          
 to the wardroom mess duty         
 forgot to unplug it

56:40.855 --> 56:43.066
and the thing was--           
      it was just fried.

56:43.108 --> 56:45.735
And none of them would admit      
 which one had done it.

56:45.777 --> 56:49.406
So the captain ordered            
 all the officers of the ship      
 to sit as a trial of inquiry

56:49.447 --> 56:51.366
to find out who'd burned out      
 the coffee machine.

56:51.408 --> 56:55.036
Which-- Look, in itself,          
 it's a silly thing.

56:55.078 --> 56:57.914
But this went on              
      for 36 hours.

56:57.956 --> 56:59.249
[Greenwald whistles]

56:59.290 --> 57:00.875
[Maryk]                           
 All ship's work suspended.

57:00.917 --> 57:03.294
And there we are, all of us,      
 we're in the wardroom.

57:03.336 --> 57:06.047
We're dying for sleep,        
      we need showers,

57:06.089 --> 57:08.633
and we're trying to figure out    
 which one of these poor bastards 
 burned out the coffee machine.

57:08.675 --> 57:11.970
And they're so scared,        
      they think whoever did it     
      is gonna get shot.

57:12.011 --> 57:13.847
They'd have sooner died   
          before they told us.

57:13.888 --> 57:16.266
And so, finally,          
          I go to the captain

57:16.307 --> 57:19.394
and I say all the officers        
 will admit that they're           
 incompetent investigators

57:19.436 --> 57:21.855
and take the hit                  
 on their fitness reports,

57:21.896 --> 57:26.109
but we can't find out             
 who left the coffee machine       
 plugged in for too long.

57:26.151 --> 57:29.279
And so he makes a mark            
 in his black book                 
 and he calls off the inquiry.

57:29.320 --> 57:32.115
It's things like that.        
      Or the water business.

57:32.157 --> 57:33.366
The water business.               
              Yes.

57:33.408 --> 57:35.743
Please describe                   
 that water business.

57:35.785 --> 57:39.914
Look, it's all in the log.    
 I know, but please describe       
 the water business.

57:39.956 --> 57:42.709
The captain                   
      restricted water use          
      from the entire crew

57:42.750 --> 57:44.711
for two days              
          in the middle             
          of a dust storm

57:44.752 --> 57:48.381
because he caught             
      one of the deck gang          
      taking a shower.

57:48.423 --> 57:51.342
Or it's plain crazy things.   
      Cheese business.

57:51.384 --> 57:52.927
The cheese business.              
      The strawberry-- Yes.

57:52.969 --> 57:56.055
Cheese business?      
              I don't recall        
              any cheese business.

57:56.097 --> 57:59.225
This was on the first ship        
 the captain was assigned to,      
 sir, as an ensign.

57:59.267 --> 58:02.437
Cheese was going missing          
 from the ship's stores.

58:02.479 --> 58:04.647
And the captain investigated      
 and he caught a sailor

58:04.689 --> 58:08.318
who'd made a duplicate key        
 to the padlock                    
 to the refrigerator.

58:08.359 --> 58:10.487
Now, for catching                 
 this cheese thief,

58:10.528 --> 58:12.697
he was given a letter             
 of commendation.

58:12.739 --> 58:15.283
This is during peacetime,         
 so naturally                      
 he's pretty proud of the thing.

58:15.325 --> 58:19.245
So when the strawberry stuff      
 started, he insisted              
 it was the same thing.

58:19.287 --> 58:20.830
And all we had to do              
 was find the guy

58:20.872 --> 58:23.791
who had made a duplicate key      
 to the wardroom fridge.

58:23.833 --> 58:25.919
But of course                 
      that's ridiculous.

58:25.960 --> 58:29.464
It was one of the guys assigned   
 to the wardroom mess again.

58:29.506 --> 58:32.217
We all knew that they'd eaten     
 this quart of strawberries.

58:32.258 --> 58:33.676
It was left over                  
 from the wardroom mess.

58:33.718 --> 58:35.762
They were entitled to it.         
 That was the custom.

58:35.803 --> 58:37.722
But when the captain              
 started to freak out              
 about those strawberries,

58:37.764 --> 58:39.599
they froze up,                    
 said they didn't                  
 know who'd eaten them.

58:39.641 --> 58:42.393
And the captain's                 
 so hot on his theory              
 he believes them.

58:42.435 --> 58:44.562
So he ordered the search          
 for the key.                      
 Yes, sir.

58:44.604 --> 58:49.317
We have never seen Captain Queeg 
 so happy before or since.

58:49.359 --> 58:52.237
He's living the cheese business   
 all over again.

58:52.278 --> 58:54.864
He organized the search himself.

58:54.906 --> 58:57.492
We collected every key            
 on that ship.

58:57.534 --> 59:01.287
We had just boxes--               
 barrels of keys.

59:01.329 --> 59:03.373
That's about 2,800 of them        
 all told,

59:03.414 --> 59:05.625
each tagged                       
 with the owner's name.

59:05.667 --> 59:09.003
And just to be safe,              
 we searched that ship             
 from stem to stern,

59:09.045 --> 59:11.673
from the radar mast           
      to the bilge.

59:11.714 --> 59:13.091
We stripped the crew naked.

59:13.132 --> 59:14.968
[Greenwald]                       
 Naked?                            
      Yes, sir. Naked.

59:15.009 --> 59:17.428
Each one of them lined up,        
 stark naked,

59:17.470 --> 59:19.722
and we shook out their clothes.

59:19.764 --> 59:22.684
We searched their lockers.        
 We searched every hole,           
 every place on that ship.

59:22.725 --> 59:25.353
We crawled under the bilge        
 and pulled out                    
 the lead ballast blocks

59:25.395 --> 59:27.105
that are 200 pounds apiece.

59:27.146 --> 59:30.316
This went on for three days.

59:30.358 --> 59:32.360
[Greenwald]                       
 Three days?                       
 [Maryk] Yes, sir.

59:32.402 --> 59:36.531
All in the name of a key          
 that never existed.

59:36.573 --> 59:41.286
So, when I saw the captain    
      sitting by the fridge,

59:41.327 --> 59:43.204
pulling keys one by one       
      from a barrel

59:43.246 --> 59:47.667
and trying them in a padlock 
      for hours on end              
      with a gleam in his eye,

59:47.709 --> 59:49.794
I gave up.

59:49.836 --> 59:53.590
And that is when              
      I showed the medical log      
      to Lieutenant Keefer.

59:54.757 --> 59:56.509
Mr. Maryk,

59:56.551 --> 59:58.761
when Lieutenant Keefer    
          finished reading          
          your medical log,

59:58.803 --> 01:00:01.097
what was              
              his first comment?

01:00:01.848 --> 01:00:03.516
Sir, I don't remember.

01:00:03.558 --> 01:00:06.311
Did he encourage you          
      to go to Admiral Williams?

01:00:06.352 --> 01:00:08.271
No, sir,                          
 I did that on my own.

01:00:08.313 --> 01:00:10.398
But he went with you 
              to the flagship.

01:00:10.440 --> 01:00:14.110
Yes, sir.                 
      So, at first,                 
      he didn't discourage you?

01:00:15.653 --> 01:00:18.448
Once we were                  
      aboard the flagship,          
      he discouraged me

01:00:18.489 --> 01:00:20.950
and said we shouldn't             
 go through it and we didn't.

01:00:20.992 --> 01:00:23.453
Would you say his testimony   
      on the subject was            
      substantially correct?

01:00:23.494 --> 01:00:25.955
Yes, sir.                         
 This was all my doing, sir.

01:00:25.997 --> 01:00:27.457
Continue your examination.

01:00:27.498 --> 01:00:29.876
Mr. Maryk,                        
 when the cyclone was over,

01:00:29.917 --> 01:00:32.795
did Commander Queeg               
 make an attempt                   
 to regain command?

01:00:32.837 --> 01:00:34.589
Yes.

01:00:34.631 --> 01:00:36.966
On the morning of the 19th,       
 after the storm had blown out.

01:00:37.008 --> 01:00:38.468
What happened?

01:00:39.844 --> 01:00:42.096
Well, I was in the chart house    
 writing up a dispatch.

01:00:42.138 --> 01:00:44.974
And?                              
      I was reporting the relief    
      to Admiral Williams.

01:00:45.016 --> 01:00:47.352
And?

01:00:47.393 --> 01:00:50.355
Captain Queeg came and asked      
 if I would go to his cabin        
 and speak to him

01:00:50.396 --> 01:00:52.315
before I sent the dispatch.

01:00:52.357 --> 01:00:55.276
So I went below               
      and we talked.

01:00:55.318 --> 01:00:57.236
And what happened?

01:00:58.529 --> 01:01:02.325
It was the same as before,    
      uh, at first.

01:01:02.367 --> 01:01:04.202
He said I'd be                    
 court-martialed for mutiny.

01:01:04.243 --> 01:01:08.289
And then he went                  
 on this long thing about          
 how much he loved the Navy,

01:01:08.331 --> 01:01:10.208
that he has no other interests,

01:01:10.249 --> 01:01:13.503
and even if                       
 he was cleared of this            
 that his record would be ruined.

01:01:13.544 --> 01:01:16.255
And I told him                
      I felt sorry for him.

01:01:16.297 --> 01:01:18.174
And I-- I really did.

01:01:19.884 --> 01:01:22.970
And that's when               
      he came out with              
      his proposal.

01:01:23.012 --> 01:01:24.430
Which?

01:01:25.807 --> 01:01:28.184
He said he wouldn't           
      write me up and report me,

01:01:28.226 --> 01:01:30.144
that he would resume          
      command of the ship

01:01:30.186 --> 01:01:33.314
and that the whole thing would    
 be written off and forgotten.

01:01:33.356 --> 01:01:35.858
And what was your reply           
 to his proposal?

01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:37.777
I was amazed.

01:01:37.819 --> 01:01:40.863
I said, Captain,                  
 the whole ship knows about it.    
 [Greenwald] Yes.

01:01:40.905 --> 01:01:43.157
It's written up               
      in the quartermaster's log.

01:01:43.199 --> 01:01:45.368
It's written up               
      in the officer                
      of the deck's log.

01:01:45.410 --> 01:01:48.913
And, uh--                     
      And he hemmed and hawed.

01:01:48.955 --> 01:01:51.165
[Greenwald]                       
 And?

01:01:51.207 --> 01:01:53.042
What happened next?

01:01:53.084 --> 01:01:55.211
Finally, he said              
      it wouldn't be                
      the first time

01:01:55.253 --> 01:01:58.172
that a rough log                  
 had been corrected                
 and fixed up after the fact.

01:01:58.214 --> 01:02:00.842
Did you remind him                
 that the alteration of logs       
 is strictly forbidden?

01:02:00.883 --> 01:02:03.428
Yes, I did.               
          And he kind of laughed.

01:02:03.469 --> 01:02:05.930
He said it was either that    
      or a court-martial            
      for mutiny for me

01:02:05.972 --> 01:02:08.766
and a black mark              
      on his record which he felt   
      he did not deserve.

01:02:08.808 --> 01:02:10.017
And what followed?

01:02:10.059 --> 01:02:11.978
He begged and he pleaded.

01:02:12.019 --> 01:02:16.607
And, uh, at one point he cried    
 and eventually got very angry

01:02:16.649 --> 01:02:18.359
and he ordered me out         
      of his cabin.

01:02:18.401 --> 01:02:20.695
That is when                  
      I sent the dispatch.

01:02:20.737 --> 01:02:25.199
Then you had the opportunity,     
 less than 24 hours later,

01:02:25.241 --> 01:02:28.911
to expunge this whole event       
 from the official records

01:02:28.953 --> 01:02:31.914
with your captain's               
 knowledge and approval.

01:02:31.956 --> 01:02:33.583
Yes, sir.

01:02:33.624 --> 01:02:36.753
Mr. Maryk,                        
 were you panicky at all           
 during the storm?

01:02:36.794 --> 01:02:38.546
No, I was not.

01:02:38.588 --> 01:02:42.592
Lieutenant, you are charged       
 with relieving                    
 your captain willfully,

01:02:42.633 --> 01:02:47.430
without authority                 
 and without justifiable cause.

01:02:47.472 --> 01:02:49.432
Did you relieve                   
 Commander Queeg willfully?

01:02:49.474 --> 01:02:52.435
Yes.                          
      I knew what I was doing.

01:02:52.477 --> 01:02:54.729
Did you relieve him               
 without authority?

01:02:54.771 --> 01:02:57.607
No, my authority is Chapter 11    
 of Navy Regulations.

01:02:57.648 --> 01:03:00.943
Did you relieve                   
 without justifiable cause?        
                  No.

01:03:00.985 --> 01:03:03.488
My justifiable cause was          
 the captain's mental breakdown

01:03:03.529 --> 01:03:05.531
at a time when the ship       
      was in danger.

01:03:05.573 --> 01:03:08.451
Thank you.                
          No further questions.

01:03:10.077 --> 01:03:13.831
Mr. Maryk,                
          this amazing interview

01:03:13.873 --> 01:03:17.668
in which the captain offered 
      to falsify official records,

01:03:17.710 --> 01:03:19.754
were there            
              any witnesses to it?

01:03:20.630 --> 01:03:22.799
We were alone in his cabin.       
 No.

01:03:22.840 --> 01:03:25.843
This incident with the mines.     
 Did anyone else                   
 see these records?

01:03:25.885 --> 01:03:27.970
Which, according to you,          
 indicated that the   Caine

01:03:28.012 --> 01:03:29.931
had departed                      
 her assigned sweep formation?

01:03:29.972 --> 01:03:32.809
Was there anything        
          in the records            
          of the ship's movements

01:03:32.850 --> 01:03:35.394
that would verify     
              that departure?

01:03:35.436 --> 01:03:37.313
Well, about an hour               
 after it happened,

01:03:37.355 --> 01:03:40.066
the captain asked                 
 to see the chart,                 
 he took it to his cabin,

01:03:40.107 --> 01:03:42.777
and when I got the log back,      
 there was no mention              
 of the incident.

01:03:42.819 --> 01:03:46.239
Right. Then you have          
      no corroboration              
      of this story.

01:03:46.280 --> 01:03:48.574
No.                           
      [clears throat]

01:03:48.616 --> 01:03:52.662
Mr. Maryk, who coined             
 the nickname Old Yellowstain?

01:03:52.703 --> 01:03:55.164
That just sprung              
      into existence.

01:03:55.206 --> 01:03:57.959
Throughout the ship   
              or just among         
              the officers?

01:03:58.000 --> 01:03:59.335
Just among the officers.

01:03:59.377 --> 01:04:01.712
You sure you didn't   
              coin it yourself?

01:04:01.754 --> 01:04:03.005
I didn't.

01:04:03.881 --> 01:04:08.803
What kind of rating           
      would you give yourself       
      for loyalty to your captain?

01:04:08.845 --> 01:04:11.305
I'd say                           
 I was a loyal officer.

01:04:12.265 --> 01:04:15.476
Did you issue                     
 a 72-hour liberty

01:04:15.518 --> 01:04:18.563
to Petty Officer Stilwell         
 in December

01:04:18.604 --> 01:04:21.649
against your captain's            
 express instructions?

01:04:21.691 --> 01:04:23.734
Yes. 
 You call that                     
 a loyal act?

01:04:23.776 --> 01:04:24.819
No.

01:04:24.861 --> 01:04:27.572
Then you admit to                 
 a disloyal act

01:04:27.613 --> 01:04:30.116
in your first days                
 as executive officer.

01:04:30.157 --> 01:04:31.576
Yes.

01:04:31.617 --> 01:04:35.538
Mr. Maryk, where did you          
 get your schooling?

01:04:35.580 --> 01:04:37.290
Public schools,   
                  San Francisco.    
              Okay.

01:04:37.331 --> 01:04:38.958
And San Francisco     
              State University.

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:41.544
And how were your grades          
 in elementary school?

01:04:41.586 --> 01:04:43.462
[scoffs]          
                  They were okay.

01:04:43.504 --> 01:04:46.841
Average? Above average?           
 Below average?

01:04:46.883 --> 01:04:47.884
Average.

01:04:47.925 --> 01:04:50.219
How about your                    
 high school grades?

01:04:50.261 --> 01:04:53.890
Well, I didn't do     
              so good there.        
              Uh, below average.

01:04:54.849 --> 01:04:57.226
What kind of courses              
 did you take in college?

01:04:57.268 --> 01:04:58.394
Business courses.

01:04:58.436 --> 01:05:00.062
Any pre-medical courses?          
                          No.

01:05:00.104 --> 01:05:03.399
Any psychology?                   
 Any psychiatry courses?           
                              No.

01:05:03.441 --> 01:05:05.359
How were your grades      
          in college?               
                          They--

01:05:05.401 --> 01:05:08.529
I got by.     
                  Below average?

01:05:09.155 --> 01:05:11.282
[Maryk]   
                          Yes.

01:05:11.324 --> 01:05:14.827
[Challee] Where did you   
          get these ideas           
          about paranoia?

01:05:14.869 --> 01:05:18.331
Prob-- Well, books.           
      And, uh... [clears throat]    
      ...a lot of research online.

01:05:18.372 --> 01:05:20.750
Books? What books?    
              Name the titles.      
              Which websites?

01:05:20.791 --> 01:05:23.336
They're medical type books        
 about mental illness,

01:05:23.377 --> 01:05:26.213
and I-I don't remember            
 the exact names of the sites.

01:05:26.255 --> 01:05:29.675
Oh. Was this                  
      your intellectual hobby,      
      reading about psychiatry?

01:05:29.717 --> 01:05:31.969
No.                       
              Well, then where did 
              you get these books?

01:05:32.011 --> 01:05:35.056
Fr-- I borrowed them              
 from, uh, ships' doctors          
 here and there.

01:05:35.097 --> 01:05:39.226
[chuckles]                    
      And with your background,     
      your scholastic record,

01:05:39.268 --> 01:05:43.189
you imagine that you understood   
 these highly technical            
 and scientific works?

01:05:43.230 --> 01:05:45.107
I got something out of them.

01:05:45.149 --> 01:05:47.401
What is                   
          a conditioned reflex?

01:05:47.443 --> 01:05:48.945
I don't know.

01:05:48.986 --> 01:05:50.905
What is schizophrenia?

01:05:50.947 --> 01:05:53.074
Uh, I think it's--                
 it's a mental illness.

01:05:53.115 --> 01:05:54.408
You think so?     
              Yes.

01:05:54.450 --> 01:05:56.911
What are its symptoms?        
                  I don't know.

01:05:56.953 --> 01:06:00.539
In fact, you don't know           
 what you're talking about         
 when you discuss mental illness.

01:06:00.581 --> 01:06:03.876
Is that right?    
 Well, you know, I never said      
 I knew much about it.

01:06:03.918 --> 01:06:04.919
[chuckles]

01:06:04.961 --> 01:06:06.504
Have you ever heard               
 the expression

01:06:06.545 --> 01:06:08.547
that a little learning            
 is a dangerous thing?

01:06:08.965 --> 01:06:10.591
Yes.

01:06:10.633 --> 01:06:12.718
You had a head full of terms      
 you didn't understand,

01:06:12.760 --> 01:06:15.262
and on that basis                 
 felt you had the right

01:06:15.304 --> 01:06:17.640
to depose                         
 a commanding officer

01:06:17.682 --> 01:06:19.767
on the grounds                    
 of mental illness.

01:06:19.809 --> 01:06:22.520
Is that right?    
 I didn't relieve Captain Queeg    
 because what the book said.

01:06:22.561 --> 01:06:26.816
I relieved him because the ship   
 was in danger of sinking.         
          No, never mind the ship.

01:06:26.857 --> 01:06:29.568
We are discussing             
      your grasp of psychiatry.     
          Mm-hmm.

01:06:29.610 --> 01:06:34.323
Did you hear the diagnosis        
 of the qualified psychiatrist     
 who examined your captain?

01:06:34.365 --> 01:06:36.158
Yes. 
 And what was                      
 their diagnosis?

01:06:36.200 --> 01:06:38.995
Was he crazy or wasn't he         
 on December 18th?

01:06:39.036 --> 01:06:40.663
They say he wasn't.

01:06:40.705 --> 01:06:43.249
But you,                  
          with your whining gripes 
          of strawberries

01:06:43.290 --> 01:06:46.419
and coffee makers,    
              know better.

01:06:46.460 --> 01:06:50.172
Mr. Maryk, who was            
      the third ranking officer     
      on your ship?

01:06:50.214 --> 01:06:51.674
Lieutenant Keefer.

01:06:51.716 --> 01:06:53.759
Was he            
                  a good officer?   
          Yes.

01:06:53.801 --> 01:06:56.512
Do you consider his mind 
          as good as yours?

01:06:56.554 --> 01:06:58.931
Yes. Uh, better. 
          Better.

01:06:58.973 --> 01:07:02.101
Did you show              
          your medical log to him? 
 Yes.

01:07:02.143 --> 01:07:05.604
Was he convinced by it    
          that the captain          
          was mentally ill?

01:07:06.188 --> 01:07:08.065
No.

01:07:08.107 --> 01:07:10.943
He talked to you          
          out of trying to have     
          the captain relieved.

01:07:10.985 --> 01:07:12.028
Yes.

01:07:12.069 --> 01:07:14.030
And yet two weeks later,

01:07:14.071 --> 01:07:17.283
despite the whole weight 
          of naval discipline,

01:07:17.324 --> 01:07:20.453
despite the arguments     
          of the next officer       
          in rank to you,

01:07:20.494 --> 01:07:22.455
a superior intellect,

01:07:22.496 --> 01:07:24.373
despite all this,

01:07:24.415 --> 01:07:27.918
you went ahead        
              and seized command    
              of your ship?

01:07:29.336 --> 01:07:31.047
I relieved Captain Queeg

01:07:31.088 --> 01:07:32.965
because he definitely             
 seemed sick

01:07:33.007 --> 01:07:35.384
on the morning                
      of the cyclone.

01:07:35.426 --> 01:07:38.679
You still believe     
              that your diagnosis   
              of Captain Queeg

01:07:38.721 --> 01:07:40.765
is superior       
                  to the doctors'?

01:07:40.806 --> 01:07:44.060
J-- O-Only about Queeg            
 on the morning                    
 of the cyclone.

01:07:46.312 --> 01:07:48.064
No more questions.

01:07:50.399 --> 01:07:51.942
No re-examination.

01:07:53.319 --> 01:07:54.904
You may step down,        
          Lieutenant.

01:08:02.787 --> 01:08:05.539
Call                              
 Lieutenant Commander Queeg.

01:08:14.924 --> 01:08:18.469
Commander, you are reminded       
 that you are still under oath.

01:08:18.511 --> 01:08:20.888
Yes, sir.                 
                      Be seated.

01:08:23.349 --> 01:08:25.684
Commander, on the morning         
 of the 19th December,

01:08:25.725 --> 01:08:28.729
did you have an interview         
 in your room                      
 with Lieutenant Maryk?

01:08:28.770 --> 01:08:30.106
Well, let's see.

01:08:30.147 --> 01:08:33.024
The 19th,                     
      the day after the storm.

01:08:33.067 --> 01:08:34.318
Yes. Yes, I did.

01:08:34.359 --> 01:08:36.946
Was the interview                 
 at your request?                  
              Yes.

01:08:36.987 --> 01:08:38.948
What was the substance            
 of the interview?

01:08:38.988 --> 01:08:41.367
Well, as I say,               
      I felt sorry for him.

01:08:41.408 --> 01:08:43.786
Hated to see him              
      ruining his life

01:08:43.828 --> 01:08:46.287
over one panicky mistake,

01:08:46.330 --> 01:08:50.542
particularly knowing          
      that it was his ambition      
      to make the Navy a career.

01:08:50.584 --> 01:08:53.629
I tried as hard as I could    
      to show him                   
      what a mistake he had made,

01:08:53.671 --> 01:08:56.090
suggested                     
      he relinquish command         
      back to me

01:08:56.131 --> 01:08:58.591
and offered to be             
      as lenient as possible

01:08:58.634 --> 01:09:00.426
when reporting                
      what had happened.

01:09:00.469 --> 01:09:03.305
You never offered                 
 not to report the incident?       
                      How could I?

01:09:03.346 --> 01:09:06.475
It had already been       
          recorded in the logs.     
          Yes.

01:09:06.517 --> 01:09:09.103
Those logs,                   
      were they handwritten,        
      typed, or what?

01:09:09.145 --> 01:09:10.938
It wouldn't have      
              made a difference.

01:09:10.979 --> 01:09:13.858
Were they handwritten,            
 Commander?                        
          Well, probably.

01:09:13.899 --> 01:09:16.068
Quartermasters log, OOD.

01:09:16.109 --> 01:09:18.194
Rough logs                        
 are usually handwritten.

01:09:18.237 --> 01:09:21.573
I can't imagine                   
 that the yeoman had time          
 to type out smooth logs,

01:09:21.615 --> 01:09:23.408
given all the excitement.

01:09:23.450 --> 01:09:26.120
Did you offer                 
      to alter the logs             
      and not report the incident?

01:09:26.162 --> 01:09:28.413
No, I did not.                    
 Alterations are not permitted.

01:09:28.455 --> 01:09:30.499
Lieutenant Maryk          
          testified under oath,     
          Commander,

01:09:30.541 --> 01:09:32.585
that you made     
                  such an offer.

01:09:32.626 --> 01:09:36.380
Not only that, but you        
      begged and pleaded with him   
      to alter the logs,

01:09:36.421 --> 01:09:39.841
in return for which       
          you promised to hush up   
          the story completely

01:09:39.884 --> 01:09:41.510
and make no report.

01:09:41.551 --> 01:09:43.220
Well, that's just                 
 not the truth.

01:09:43.261 --> 01:09:45.639
There isn't any truth     
          in it at all?

01:09:45.680 --> 01:09:48.725
It's a complete distortion        
 of what I've said.                
 My version is the exact truth.

01:09:48.767 --> 01:09:51.687
You deny the proposal     
          to alter the logs         
          and hush up the story.

01:09:51.729 --> 01:09:53.647
Yes. I deny it completely.

01:09:53.689 --> 01:09:56.483
Th-That's the part                
 that he's made up,                
 the crying and the pleading.

01:09:56.525 --> 01:09:57.818
It's fantastic.

01:09:57.860 --> 01:09:59.653
You're accusing Mr. Maryk     
      of perjury.

01:09:59.695 --> 01:10:01.447
I-I'm not accusing him--

01:10:01.488 --> 01:10:02.823
[laughs]

01:10:02.865 --> 01:10:04.950
He's accused of enough            
 as it stands.

01:10:04.992 --> 01:10:07.786
I'm just saying you'll hear       
 a lot of strange things           
 about me from Maryk.

01:10:07.828 --> 01:10:10.206
Th-That's all I'm saying.

01:10:10.247 --> 01:10:13.542
Isn't it obvious, Commander,      
 that one of you is not telling    
 the truth about this meeting?

01:10:13.584 --> 01:10:16.629
Well, it appears so.              
              Can you prove that    
              it isn't you?

01:10:16.670 --> 01:10:20.216
Only by citing                    
 a clean record of 21 years        
 as a naval officer

01:10:20.257 --> 01:10:24.053
over the word of                  
 a man standing trial              
 for a mutinous act.

01:10:25.763 --> 01:10:30.559
Commander, did you ever           
 receive $1,000 from               
 Lieutenant Junior Grade Keith?

01:10:30.601 --> 01:10:32.853
Uh, I don't recall offhand.

01:10:32.895 --> 01:10:35.397
He testified you did.             
              I did?                
              On what occasion?

01:10:35.439 --> 01:10:38.901
On the occasion of the loss   
      of a crate of yours           
      in the Port of Oman.

01:10:38.943 --> 01:10:41.195
Oh, y-yes. Okay.              
      [chuckling] I remember that.

01:10:41.237 --> 01:10:43.906
That's over a year ago,   
          December thereabouts.

01:10:43.948 --> 01:10:46.575
He was responsible    
              for the loss.

01:10:46.617 --> 01:10:50.246
Well, insisted        
              on paying for it,     
              a-a-and so he did.

01:10:50.287 --> 01:10:53.290
And what was in this crate        
 that cost $1,000?

01:10:53.332 --> 01:10:56.043
Well, uniforms, books,

01:10:56.085 --> 01:10:59.088
n-navigating instruments,     
      the usual things.

01:10:59.129 --> 01:11:00.923
How was Keith responsible?

01:11:00.965 --> 01:11:03.217
Well, he was the boat officer.    
 He was responsible for loading.

01:11:03.259 --> 01:11:06.595
He issued foolish,        
          contradictory orders      
          that rattled the men.

01:11:06.637 --> 01:11:08.681
They dropped the crate        
      into the water and it sank.

01:11:08.722 --> 01:11:11.892
A wooden crate,                   
 full of clothes, sank.

01:11:11.934 --> 01:11:14.270
It had other things in it.

01:11:14.311 --> 01:11:16.563
Souvenir coral rocks,             
 for example.                      
                      [chuckles]

01:11:16.605 --> 01:11:20.442
Commander, wasn't the--   
          the crate entirely full   
          of bottles of booze?

01:11:20.484 --> 01:11:22.611
Certainly not.

01:11:22.653 --> 01:11:26.782
Lieutenant Keith testified    
      that he paid you $1,000       
      for a crate full of liquor.

01:11:26.824 --> 01:11:30.411
Well, you'll hear a lot of        
 strange distortions from Keith.   
 A-And from Maryk.

01:11:30.452 --> 01:11:33.789
They're the two culprits here.    
 They're apt to make all kinds     
 of strange statements.

01:11:33.831 --> 01:11:35.582
You make this crate   
              yourself?

01:11:35.624 --> 01:11:38.127
No, a man                         
 from the engine room did.         
                  What's his name?

01:11:38.168 --> 01:11:40.212
I don't recall. It'll be          
 in the personnel records.

01:11:40.254 --> 01:11:43.048
He's been gone from the ship      
 for quite some time.              
          Okay, where is he now?

01:11:43.924 --> 01:11:45.718
Uh, I-I don't know.

01:11:45.759 --> 01:11:49.138
Because you don't know            
 what his name is?                 
                  No.

01:11:49.179 --> 01:11:54.184
Was it Engineman Second Class     
 Otis F. Langhorn, sir?

01:11:54.226 --> 01:11:56.520
L... Langhorn?

01:11:56.562 --> 01:11:57.896
Yes.

01:11:58.522 --> 01:11:59.773
Langhorn, yeah.

01:11:59.815 --> 01:12:01.984
Well, th-that         
              sounds about right.

01:12:02.026 --> 01:12:06.905
There's an Otis F. Langhorn,      
 engineman first class,            
 in transit right now.

01:12:06.947 --> 01:12:09.575
Defense has arranged to           
 subpoena him if necessary.

01:12:09.616 --> 01:12:11.785
Are you sure          
              it's the same one?

01:12:11.827 --> 01:12:14.872
Well, it says 20 months           
 aboard the   Caine.                 
 It's got your signature upon it.

01:12:14.913 --> 01:12:16.749
Would it be useful                
 to have him called, sir?

01:12:16.790 --> 01:12:19.877
Objection                     
      to this entire irrelevancy    
      about the crate

01:12:19.918 --> 01:12:22.004
and request it be stricken        
 from the record.

01:12:22.046 --> 01:12:24.173
The witness's credibility         
 is being established.

01:12:24.214 --> 01:12:27.760
I put it to the court, sir,       
 that nothing could be             
 more relevant to this trial.

01:12:28.719 --> 01:12:30.179
Overruled.

01:12:30.220 --> 01:12:32.598
Court stenographer            
      will repeat the question.

01:12:32.639 --> 01:12:35.517
[stenographer]                
      "Would it be useful to        
      have him subpoenaed, sir?"

01:12:35.559 --> 01:12:39.188
Well, the real question is,       
 which crate                       
 did Langhorn nail up?

01:12:39.229 --> 01:12:41.482
I-I now recall                    
 having two crates.

01:12:41.523 --> 01:12:45.444
Oh, well,                         
 this is new information           
 not mentioned by Keith.

01:12:45.486 --> 01:12:47.613
Did Langhorn nail up              
 both crates, sir?

01:12:47.654 --> 01:12:51.492
I-I can't-- I can't recall        
 if I had two crates               
 on th-that occasion

01:12:51.533 --> 01:12:54.036
or two crates                     
 on two separate occasions.

01:12:54.078 --> 01:12:58.374
It's been a long time             
 and I've had a strenuous year     
 of command from ports of storm.

01:12:58.415 --> 01:13:00.876
I-- I just--                      
 I can't be clear.

01:13:00.918 --> 01:13:04.296
Commander,                        
 there are a number of issues      
 in this trial

01:13:04.338 --> 01:13:06.256
which turn on                     
 the issue of credibility

01:13:06.298 --> 01:13:08.384
between yourself                  
 and other officers.

01:13:08.425 --> 01:13:11.136
If you wish,                      
 I can request a quick             
 little five-minute recess

01:13:11.178 --> 01:13:14.431
while you clear your mind         
 as best you can about             
 the matter of this crate.

01:13:14.473 --> 01:13:17.518
No, no, that won't be necessary. 
 Just give me some time to think.

01:13:17.559 --> 01:13:19.395
Please.                           
          Please.

01:13:22.147 --> 01:13:23.732
Uh...

01:13:24.775 --> 01:13:26.443
Um...

01:13:27.194 --> 01:13:28.904
Uh...

01:13:29.947 --> 01:13:33.200
Ah, o-okay.                       
 I-I've got it straight now.

01:13:33.242 --> 01:13:35.536
Mm-hmm.                           
      I misspoke.

01:13:35.577 --> 01:13:40.165
Uh, San Diego, 2014,              
 I lost a crate                    
 in similar circumstances.

01:13:40.207 --> 01:13:42.209
That was the crate                
 with the clothes in it

01:13:42.251 --> 01:13:46.004
and the crate that Keith lost     
 did contain liquor.

01:13:46.046 --> 01:13:49.091
Entirely full of liquor.          
              Well, I suppose so.

01:13:49.133 --> 01:13:51.885
You transported this              
 on your ship.

01:13:51.927 --> 01:13:53.345
You are aware of                  
 Navy Regulations, sir.

01:13:53.387 --> 01:13:55.431
Of course I'm aware   
              of regulations.

01:13:55.472 --> 01:13:57.599
Th-The crate was sealed   
          before I got under way.

01:13:57.641 --> 01:13:59.768
I gave it                 
          the same locked stowage   
          that I did

01:13:59.810 --> 01:14:02.271
the medicinal brandy,         
      three years' steady duty.

01:14:02.312 --> 01:14:07.109
I gave myself this leeway     
      as the captain of the   Caine, 
      which was a common practice.

01:14:07.151 --> 01:14:11.655
I do believe that rank        
      has its privileges,           
      as they say, and, well, uh--

01:14:11.697 --> 01:14:14.575
I-I didn't mean to                
 conceal it from the court.

01:14:14.616 --> 01:14:16.452
It's not something                
 I'm ashamed of.

01:14:16.493 --> 01:14:18.996
I just got the two crates         
 mixed up in my mind.

01:14:19.037 --> 01:14:20.581
Lieutenant Maryk      
              also testified, sir,

01:14:20.622 --> 01:14:22.458
that you gave         
              all the orders        
              to the boat crew

01:14:22.499 --> 01:14:24.251
which resulted                
      in the loss of the crate.

01:14:24.293 --> 01:14:26.420
[chuckles]                        
 Well, that's a lie.

01:14:26.462 --> 01:14:29.173
And that you refused              
 to sign his leave papers          
 until he paid you for that loss.

01:14:29.214 --> 01:14:31.300
[Queeg]                   
          And that is another lie.

01:14:32.759 --> 01:14:35.888
Commander, during the period 
      when the   Caine                
      was sweeping for mines

01:14:35.929 --> 01:14:37.639
off the Straits of Hormuz,

01:14:37.681 --> 01:14:39.892
did you steam over                
 and cut your own tow line?

01:14:39.933 --> 01:14:41.393
[Challee]     
                      Objection!

01:14:41.435 --> 01:14:43.729
This tow line business        
      is the last straw.

01:14:43.770 --> 01:14:45.981
The tactics                   
      of the defense counsel        
      are an outrage

01:14:46.023 --> 01:14:47.816
on the dignity                
      of these proceedings.

01:14:47.858 --> 01:14:49.651
He is systematically          
      turning this trial

01:14:49.693 --> 01:14:51.737
into a court-martial          
      of Commander Queeg.

01:14:51.778 --> 01:14:53.322
[Greenwald]           
              Please the court,

01:14:53.363 --> 01:14:55.324
the trial counsel believes        
 she has a prima facie case

01:14:55.365 --> 01:14:57.951
based on the report           
      of two psychiatrists.

01:14:57.993 --> 01:14:59.620
Now, I believe it is 
              up to the court

01:14:59.661 --> 01:15:02.164
and not                   
          two shore-bound doctors, 
          however brilliant,

01:15:02.206 --> 01:15:05.417
to decide whether             
      the captain of the   Caine      
      was mentally well enough

01:15:05.459 --> 01:15:10.047
to retain his self-control        
 and his post during a cyclone.

01:15:10.088 --> 01:15:12.049
The objection is overruled.

01:15:12.090 --> 01:15:14.051
The witness                   
      will answer the question.

01:15:14.092 --> 01:15:18.013
Okay, well, here's the story      
 on that particular slander.

01:15:19.014 --> 01:15:20.807
Stilwell                          
 was a-a-at the helm,

01:15:20.849 --> 01:15:23.268
a dreamy, unreliable man

01:15:23.310 --> 01:15:26.813
who failed to warn me             
 that we were coming around        
 the full 360 degrees.

01:15:26.855 --> 01:15:30.108
I was the one who recognized      
 what was happening,               
 reversed course immediately.

01:15:30.150 --> 01:15:34.071
We did not go over the tow line. 
 I-It parted in the tight turn.

01:15:34.112 --> 01:15:37.407
Weren't you reprimanding          
 a petty officer named Urban       
 at length

01:15:37.449 --> 01:15:42.496
for having his shirttail out      
 while your ship was               
 turning 360 degrees, sir?

01:15:42.538 --> 01:15:44.540
Who told you that?    
              Keith again?          
 Answer the question, please.

01:15:44.581 --> 01:15:45.999
It's a malicious lie,         
      of course.

01:15:46.041 --> 01:15:48.043
Was Urban on the bridge?          
              Yes.

01:15:48.085 --> 01:15:50.837
Was his shirttail out?            
      Yes, and I reprimanded him.   
      Took all of two seconds.

01:15:50.879 --> 01:15:52.839
It's not like I dwell         
      on these sort of things.

01:15:52.881 --> 01:15:54.967
But now that you've brought   
      the shirttail thing up,

01:15:55.008 --> 01:15:58.887
I'd like to point out     
          that Ensign Keith,        
          a department head,

01:15:58.929 --> 01:16:01.557
was responsible       
              for enforcing         
              uniform regulations

01:16:01.598 --> 01:16:03.850
and completely screwed    
          the whole job up.

01:16:03.892 --> 01:16:06.853
When I took over the ship,    
      it was like some              
      third-world navy,

01:16:06.895 --> 01:16:09.898
and I bored down on Keith     
      to look out for things        
      like shirttails.

01:16:09.940 --> 01:16:13.277
And, well, maybe              
      that's one of the reasons     
      that he hates me so much

01:16:13.318 --> 01:16:18.407
and insists on circulating    
      this nonsense about me        
      cutting the tow line.

01:16:18.448 --> 01:16:21.201
Did you drop a yellow dye marker 
 off the Straits of Hormuz?

01:16:21.243 --> 01:16:23.453
No, I, uh-- Maybe.    
              I-I don't recall.

01:16:23.495 --> 01:16:25.581
Do you recall                     
 what your first mission was?

01:16:25.622 --> 01:16:29.751
Well, uh, to detect           
      and destroy mines             
      in the Straits of Hormuz.

01:16:29.793 --> 01:16:31.878
And did you fulfill               
 that mission?                     
                      Yes.

01:16:31.920 --> 01:16:34.339
So why did you drop   
              the dye marker?       
 I'm not saying that I did.

01:16:34.381 --> 01:16:37.342
But if I had,                     
 it would have been to mark        
 a mine that we had detected.

01:16:37.384 --> 01:16:41.388
Commander,                    
      didn't you drop the marker    
      and retire at high speed,

01:16:41.430 --> 01:16:44.224
taking the   Caine              
      out of its assigned           
      sweep pattern?

01:16:44.266 --> 01:16:48.604
Now, didn't you do this           
 to avoid contact with             
 a dangerous underwater mine

01:16:48.645 --> 01:16:50.355
and leave it      
                  for another ship 
                  to handle?

01:16:50.397 --> 01:16:52.441
The question is abusive           
 and flagrantly leading.

01:16:52.482 --> 01:16:56.361
I withdraw my last question       
 on account of                     
 the witness's dim memory.

01:16:56.403 --> 01:16:58.530
I'll proceed                      
 to more recent events.

01:16:58.572 --> 01:17:01.074
[officer] Court desires       
      to question the witness.

01:17:01.116 --> 01:17:02.951
Commander Queeg,

01:17:02.993 --> 01:17:05.537
in view of the implications       
 in this line of testimony,

01:17:05.579 --> 01:17:07.956
I urge you                        
 to search your memory             
 for correct answers.

01:17:07.998 --> 01:17:10.334
Well, I certainly             
      am trying, sir.

01:17:10.375 --> 01:17:13.920
These are very fine points,       
 and I've had a number of arduous 
 missions since that storm.

01:17:13.962 --> 01:17:17.049
And th-then there's,              
 well, all of this business.

01:17:17.090 --> 01:17:18.717
I appreciate that.

01:17:18.759 --> 01:17:21.553
But it will facilitate justice    
 if you can remember enough

01:17:21.595 --> 01:17:24.306
to give a few definite answers    
 on points of fact.

01:17:24.348 --> 01:17:29.019
First of all, did you depart      
 your assigned sector              
 due to equipment problems?

01:17:31.063 --> 01:17:33.482
Yes. Yes.                         
 Okay-- Okay, I-I remember.

01:17:33.523 --> 01:17:35.776
Yes,                              
 that was the case here.

01:17:35.817 --> 01:17:39.821
So you departed the pattern       
 rather than try to repair         
 or troubleshoot the equipment?

01:17:39.863 --> 01:17:42.991
But... [scoffs]                   
 ...an active mine                 
 had been detected.

01:17:43.033 --> 01:17:47.079
Is that why you dropped           
 the dye marker?                   
 There was a safety factor.

01:17:47.120 --> 01:17:51.249
Uh, it didn't make sense to me    
 to try and detonate mines         
 using defective gear.

01:17:51.291 --> 01:17:54.836
But I wanted every vessel         
 in the area to know exactly       
 where that mine was,

01:17:54.878 --> 01:17:56.838
s-so I marked it.

01:17:56.880 --> 01:17:59.341
Now, if I erred on the side       
 of being overcautious,            
 well, I-I'm sorry.

01:17:59.383 --> 01:18:03.136
But then again, sir,              
 I don't think you can err         
 on the side of safety.

01:18:03.178 --> 01:18:05.055
Did you have the conn?            
                      Well, no.

01:18:05.097 --> 01:18:07.724
A-As I recall,            
          Maryk was on the conn.

01:18:07.766 --> 01:18:11.186
And I also recall                 
 warning him not to stray          
 too far out of formation.

01:18:11.228 --> 01:18:16.775
But we did need to leave room     
 for other ships to come in        
 and deal with that mine.

01:18:16.817 --> 01:18:19.069
Well, how much room?              
 I don't remember exactly.

01:18:19.111 --> 01:18:22.739
I-I just know that                
 we had strayed outside            
 of our assigned sector,

01:18:22.781 --> 01:18:26.034
and then, well,                   
 I pulled him aside                
 and admonished him.

01:18:26.076 --> 01:18:29.204
Didn't you direct him             
 to return to station              
 immediately?

01:18:29.246 --> 01:18:30.831
Sir, everything               
      was happening very fast.

01:18:30.872 --> 01:18:33.375
We had to mark the area           
 and then get out of there

01:18:33.417 --> 01:18:36.336
and make room for other ships     
 to come into the area,            
 as I said.

01:18:36.378 --> 01:18:39.089
These are your factual            
 recollections, Commander?

01:18:39.131 --> 01:18:41.383
Those are the facts, sir.

01:18:43.051 --> 01:18:44.428
Resume your examination.

01:18:44.469 --> 01:18:46.096
Commander,                        
 did you make it a practice

01:18:46.138 --> 01:18:48.807
to retire to your room            
 during minesweeping operations?

01:18:48.849 --> 01:18:51.727
Well, that's                  
      an insulting question.        
      The answer is no.

01:18:51.768 --> 01:18:54.104
I had to be on                
      every side of that bridge     
      at all times.

01:18:54.146 --> 01:18:59.025
I-I had Maryk as a navigator      
 and Keith as an officer of        
 the deck at general quarters.

01:18:59.067 --> 01:19:01.737
Invariably, they'd squirrel   
      over to the same side         
      of the bridge

01:19:01.778 --> 01:19:05.157
and I'd have to be captain,       
 navigator and officer of          
 the deck all rolled up into one.

01:19:05.198 --> 01:19:07.951
That's why I had to go        
      from one side of the bridge   
      to the other all the time.

01:19:07.993 --> 01:19:10.162
And that's the truth.

01:19:10.203 --> 01:19:12.748
I don't care how many damn lies   
 have been told about me           
 in this courtroom.

01:19:12.789 --> 01:19:14.958
The court                     
      will question the witness.

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:18.837
Sir, the witness                  
 is obviously and understandably   
 agitated by this ordeal

01:19:18.879 --> 01:19:21.590
and I request a recess    
          to give him               
          a breathing space.

01:19:21.631 --> 01:19:23.884
I'm not agitated              
      in the least.

01:19:23.925 --> 01:19:26.094
I'm glad to answer            
      any and all questions.

01:19:26.136 --> 01:19:28.054
[marbles clacking]

01:19:28.096 --> 01:19:31.099
In fact,                          
 I-I demand the opportunity        
 to set the record straight

01:19:31.141 --> 01:19:35.645
for any derogatory statements     
 made about me in testimony        
 that's gone before.

01:19:35.687 --> 01:19:39.232
I didn't make a single mistake    
 in the 15 months                  
 I was aboard the   Caine,

01:19:39.274 --> 01:19:41.193
and I-I can prove it.

01:19:41.234 --> 01:19:43.528
I've had a spotless record        
 up until now

01:19:43.570 --> 01:19:45.655
and I don't want it   
              being discredited

01:19:45.697 --> 01:19:49.451
by these lies and distortions     
 told by these disloyal officers.

01:19:49.493 --> 01:19:52.662
Commander,                    
      would you like a recess?

01:19:52.704 --> 01:19:53.747
Certainly not.

01:19:53.789 --> 01:19:56.666
In fact, if I had                 
 any say in this,

01:19:56.708 --> 01:19:58.960
I would ask                       
 there be no recess.

01:19:59.002 --> 01:20:02.130
[marbles continue clacking]       
                      [officer]     
                      Very well.

01:20:03.048 --> 01:20:05.175
I simply want to ask,

01:20:05.217 --> 01:20:08.553
if the performance                
 of these two officers             
 was so unspeakably bad,

01:20:08.595 --> 01:20:10.388
why did you tolerate it?

01:20:10.430 --> 01:20:13.475
Why didn't you beach them         
 or rotate them                    
 out of your command?

01:20:15.852 --> 01:20:19.981
Well, this is gonna sound         
 strange to you, sir, but,

01:20:20.023 --> 01:20:24.778
well, the truth is                
 I'm-I'm a softhearted man

01:20:24.820 --> 01:20:26.822
and not many people               
 know that.

01:20:26.863 --> 01:20:29.491
But I wanted to keep      
          them under-- under eye

01:20:29.533 --> 01:20:32.619
to try and train them up,     
      make them good officers.

01:20:32.661 --> 01:20:36.665
L-Last thing I wanted to do       
 was wreck their careers.

01:20:36.706 --> 01:20:41.253
A concern they certainly          
 didn't share for me.              
 E-Either one of them.

01:20:44.214 --> 01:20:46.508
Commander, on the morning         
 of the 18th of December,

01:20:46.550 --> 01:20:48.385
the exact moment                  
 you were relieved of command,

01:20:48.426 --> 01:20:50.011
was the   Caine                     
 in the last extremity?

01:20:50.053 --> 01:20:52.806
Certainly not.            
 Was it in grave danger            
 at that moment?

01:20:52.848 --> 01:20:55.517
Absolutely not.               
      I was in complete control     
      of the ship.

01:20:55.559 --> 01:20:58.019
And did you inform                
 any of your other officers        
 of your intention

01:20:58.061 --> 01:21:00.355
to change course,             
      come north at ten o'clock,

01:21:00.397 --> 01:21:02.858
15 minutes                
          after Lieutenant Maryk    
          relieved you of command?

01:21:02.899 --> 01:21:05.569
Yes, yes.                     
      I made that statement         
      and that was my intention.

01:21:05.610 --> 01:21:09.447
Then Lieutenant Maryk's decision 
 to come north was not             
 a panicky, irrational blunder.

01:21:09.489 --> 01:21:11.950
His panicky blunder   
              was relieving me.

01:21:11.992 --> 01:21:14.536
I kept him from making    
          any disastrous mistakes   
          thereafter.

01:21:14.578 --> 01:21:16.705
I wasn't trying       
              to vindicate myself.

01:21:16.746 --> 01:21:20.333
Commander, have you seen          
 Lieutenant Maryk's medical log?

01:21:20.375 --> 01:21:22.377
Yes. [chuckles]

01:21:22.419 --> 01:21:26.006
Yes, I've read                
      that interesting document.    
      Yes, sir, I have.

01:21:26.047 --> 01:21:29.050
Biggest conglomeration    
          of lies and distortions   
          and half-truths

01:21:29.092 --> 01:21:30.635
I've ever seen.

01:21:30.677 --> 01:21:32.345
But I'm extremely glad    
          that you've asked

01:21:32.387 --> 01:21:35.181
'cause I wanna        
              get my side of it     
              all on the record.

01:21:35.223 --> 01:21:36.641
Please.

01:21:36.683 --> 01:21:39.060
Please give us your version       
 of any comments

01:21:39.102 --> 01:21:41.062
factually related                 
 to episodes in the log.

01:21:41.104 --> 01:21:43.732
Okay, well,                   
      starting right with           
      that strawberry business.

01:21:43.773 --> 01:21:45.901
The real truth            
          is that I was betrayed,

01:21:45.942 --> 01:21:48.028
d-double-crossed          
          by my executive officer

01:21:48.069 --> 01:21:50.614
and this precious gentleman, 
      Mr. Keith,

01:21:50.655 --> 01:21:52.574
who between them          
          corrupted my wardroom

01:21:52.616 --> 01:21:54.618
so I was one man          
          against the whole ship.

01:21:54.659 --> 01:21:56.578
No support                
          from my officers, okay?

01:21:56.620 --> 01:21:59.039
[chuckles] Now, you take          
 that strawberry business.

01:21:59.080 --> 01:22:03.460
Why, if that wasn't a case of     
 outright conspiracy to protect    
 a malefactor from justice.

01:22:03.501 --> 01:22:05.712
Maryk carefully leaves out        
 the little fact

01:22:05.754 --> 01:22:09.215
that I had conclusively proved    
 by a process of elimination

01:22:09.257 --> 01:22:11.092
that someone                      
 had a key to the fridge.

01:22:11.134 --> 01:22:14.596
Now, he says the messmen 
          ate the strawberries.

01:22:14.638 --> 01:22:16.598
But if I wanted       
              to take the trouble,

01:22:16.640 --> 01:22:19.476
I could prove to this court       
 categorically                     
 that they couldn't have.

01:22:19.517 --> 01:22:21.436
I-It's the water business         
 all over again.

01:22:21.478 --> 01:22:24.439
Like when the crew                
 was taking showers                
 seven times a day

01:22:24.481 --> 01:22:28.234
and I tried to initiate           
 the simplest principles           
 of water conservation.

01:22:28.276 --> 01:22:30.779
But, oh, no, Mr. Maryk,           
 the hero of the crew,

01:22:30.820 --> 01:22:33.365
wanted to go right on             
 coddling them.

01:22:33.406 --> 01:22:36.117
Well, you take                    
 that coffee business.

01:22:36.159 --> 01:22:37.953
Well-- No.

01:22:37.994 --> 01:22:39.788
[laughs]                          
 No. Excuse me.

01:22:39.829 --> 01:22:42.248
Sorry, sir.

01:22:42.290 --> 01:22:44.960
Strawberry thing first.           
 Okay.

01:22:46.252 --> 01:22:48.463
Everything hinged                 
 on a thorough search              
 for the key,

01:22:48.505 --> 01:22:52.133
and that's when Maryk             
 and, as usual, with help          
 from Mr. Keith, fudged it.

01:22:52.175 --> 01:22:54.844
Went through                      
 a lot of phony motions,           
 didn't prove anything.

01:22:54.886 --> 01:22:57.514
Like thinking                     
 that the burning out              
 of the coffee makers,

01:22:57.555 --> 01:22:59.432
which were government property,

01:22:59.474 --> 01:23:01.434
was some kind of joke.

01:23:01.476 --> 01:23:03.979
And that was                      
 the attitude of everybody         
 from Maryk on down.

01:23:04.020 --> 01:23:06.564
No-- No sense                     
 of responsibility.

01:23:06.606 --> 01:23:09.234
And I kept emphasizing            
 over and over

01:23:09.275 --> 01:23:12.654
that all of these things          
 were gonna have to be             
 accounted for.

01:23:12.696 --> 01:23:14.823
[groans]                          
 It was a constant battle.

01:23:14.864 --> 01:23:16.574
Always--                          
 Always the same thing.

01:23:16.616 --> 01:23:19.369
Maryk and Keith                   
 undermining my authority,         
 always arguing.

01:23:19.411 --> 01:23:23.832
Now, I wanted--                   
 I wanted to train Keith up        
 to be a good officer,

01:23:23.873 --> 01:23:26.501
but I was stabbed                 
 in the back by--

01:23:29.879 --> 01:23:31.423
Well...

01:23:32.298 --> 01:23:34.009
[chuckles]

01:23:34.050 --> 01:23:39.014
Well, I-- I think I've covered    
 that strawberry business.

01:23:39.055 --> 01:23:41.141
And, oh, yes,                     
 the mess account business.

01:23:41.182 --> 01:23:44.811
Well, I had to                    
 watch them like a hawk,           
 and believe me, I did.

01:23:44.853 --> 01:23:47.355
[chuckles] Didn't sneak           
 any fast ones by me.

01:23:47.397 --> 01:23:49.357
It wasn't for                 
      a lack of trying.

01:23:49.399 --> 01:23:51.985
Instead of paying attention       
 to their accounts                 
 and their inventories,

01:23:52.027 --> 01:23:53.862
which I would have to go          
 over again and again--

01:23:53.903 --> 01:23:56.698
Always a few pennies short        
 or a couple dollars over.

01:23:56.740 --> 01:24:01.578
But what do they care about       
 keeping accurate records?         
 Let the captain worry about it.

01:24:01.619 --> 01:24:03.872
Well, by God, I did.

01:24:03.913 --> 01:24:08.585
I-I defy anyone to find           
 a single wardroom mess statement 
 or ship service inventory

01:24:08.626 --> 01:24:11.171
filed aboard the USS   Caine        
 while I was captain

01:24:11.212 --> 01:24:13.631
that had a mistake                
 of a single, solitary cent.

01:24:13.673 --> 01:24:18.136
And by that, I mean, I defy       
 a certified public accountant     
 to do it. Okay?

01:24:18.178 --> 01:24:19.804
Well, what else?

01:24:19.846 --> 01:24:21.973
[muttering]                       
 There's so much bullshit

01:24:22.015 --> 01:24:25.018
in that precious log          
      of Mr. Maryk's.

01:24:25.060 --> 01:24:28.521
Oh, yes! [laughs]                 
 Th-The movie business.

01:24:28.563 --> 01:24:30.982
Okay,                             
 no respect for command.

01:24:31.024 --> 01:24:33.443
Th-That was the whole trouble     
 with that ship.

01:24:33.485 --> 01:24:37.322
The movie operator, who had       
 a disrespectful manner anyways,

01:24:37.363 --> 01:24:41.409
started the movie                 
 without waiting for the arrival   
 of the commanding officer.

01:24:41.451 --> 01:24:43.912
Out of that whole ship's crew,    
 officers and men,

01:24:43.953 --> 01:24:48.750
did one person stand up           
 and call a halt or even notice    
 that the captain wasn't present?

01:24:48.792 --> 01:24:51.920
I missed those movies             
 more than they did.

01:24:52.962 --> 01:24:55.757
I banned them,                    
 and, by God, I'd do it again.

01:24:55.799 --> 01:24:59.344
Wh-What was I supposed to do,     
 start issuing them all            
 letters of commendation

01:24:59.385 --> 01:25:02.931
for this gratuitous insult        
 to the commanding officer?

01:25:02.972 --> 01:25:04.099
[laughs]

01:25:04.140 --> 01:25:06.601
It's not like                     
 I took it personal.

01:25:06.643 --> 01:25:10.105
Uh, it's the principle.           
 The principle of respect          
 for the command.

01:25:10.146 --> 01:25:13.942
That principle was dead           
 when I came aboard that ship      
 and I brought it to life.

01:25:13.983 --> 01:25:15.985
And I nagged and I bitched        
 and I hollered,

01:25:16.027 --> 01:25:18.613
and, by God, I made it stick      
 while I was captain!

01:25:20.156 --> 01:25:22.492
Uh, and as I-- as I say,

01:25:22.534 --> 01:25:24.786
it wasn't                         
 just the coffee makers.

01:25:24.828 --> 01:25:26.496
It was a matter of respect.

01:25:26.538 --> 01:25:29.082
When I ask a sailor a question,   
 I want a straight answer.

01:25:29.124 --> 01:25:31.334
Nobody's gonna get away           
 with this shifty evasion,

01:25:31.376 --> 01:25:34.420
if I have to hold                 
 a court of inquiry                
 for a week.

01:25:34.462 --> 01:25:37.215
What do I care                    
 about strawberries?               
 It's a question of principle.

01:25:37.257 --> 01:25:39.175
Stealing is stealing.

01:25:39.759 --> 01:25:41.636
And on my ship--

01:25:45.682 --> 01:25:49.644
Well, it's not like we got        
 a lot of nice treats anyway.

01:25:49.686 --> 01:25:53.815
Uh... if we ever did              
 get something pleasant            
 once in a blue moon,

01:25:53.857 --> 01:25:55.984
like--                            
 like strawberries, well,

01:25:56.025 --> 01:25:59.070
it was outrageous that            
 I couldn't have a second helping 
 if I felt like it.

01:25:59.112 --> 01:26:01.489
I wasn't gonna let them           
 get away with it, and I didn't.

01:26:01.531 --> 01:26:05.493
By God, I never                   
 let anything like that            
 happen on that ship again!

01:26:14.335 --> 01:26:16.337
[mutters]

01:26:16.379 --> 01:26:18.214
As I say, I--

01:26:18.256 --> 01:26:19.465
Okay, um...

01:26:20.383 --> 01:26:23.678
H-How many of these things    
      have I covered?

01:26:23.720 --> 01:26:27.223
I-- I can only roughly        
      do this by memory.

01:26:27.265 --> 01:26:29.976
If you ask me                 
      specific questions,           
      I'll--

01:26:30.018 --> 01:26:33.229
I'll tackle those             
      one by one by one.

01:26:34.439 --> 01:26:36.858
That won't be necessary, sir.

01:26:37.984 --> 01:26:39.986
That was very thorough.

01:26:41.029 --> 01:26:42.530
Thank you.

01:26:47.327 --> 01:26:51.206
I draw                    
          the court's attention     
          to Exhibit 12.

01:26:54.083 --> 01:26:56.211
Commander, I show you     
          an authenticated copy

01:26:56.252 --> 01:26:59.130
of a fitness report   
              that you wrote        
              for Lieutenant Maryk

01:26:59.172 --> 01:27:01.466
July 1, 2022.

01:27:01.507 --> 01:27:03.885
Do you recognize it   
              as such?

01:27:06.346 --> 01:27:08.014
Y-Yes.

01:27:08.056 --> 01:27:10.850
And by this time          
          had the following events 
          occurred--

01:27:10.892 --> 01:27:14.812
the water shortage,   
              the coffee maker      
              investigation,

01:27:14.854 --> 01:27:17.649
the banning of the movies,    
      the Internet

01:27:17.690 --> 01:27:19.734
and other events?

01:27:21.527 --> 01:27:23.655
Yes, I believe so.

01:27:23.696 --> 01:27:28.910
Please read your comments     
      on Lieutenant Maryk, July 1.

01:27:29.744 --> 01:27:32.121
Well, n-not being vindictive,

01:27:32.163 --> 01:27:36.459
I-I don't write down              
 every single, solitary instance.

01:27:36.501 --> 01:27:39.045
A fitness report                  
 goes into a man's record,

01:27:39.087 --> 01:27:42.924
and, well, I've always            
 tried to go easy on them.

01:27:42.966 --> 01:27:44.968
A-Always have, always will.

01:27:45.009 --> 01:27:46.719
I appreciate that, sir.

01:27:46.761 --> 01:27:48.721
Please read the comments.

01:27:54.602 --> 01:27:56.771
"This officer has,                
 if anything,

01:27:56.813 --> 01:27:59.941
improved in                       
 his performance of duty

01:27:59.983 --> 01:28:02.944
since the last fitness report.

01:28:03.903 --> 01:28:07.198
He is consistently loyal,     
      unflagging,

01:28:07.240 --> 01:28:11.619
thorough, courageous      
          and efficient.

01:28:12.870 --> 01:28:15.206
He is considered at present

01:28:15.248 --> 01:28:19.627
fully qualified for command       
 of a 1,200-ton MCM.

01:28:21.087 --> 01:28:26.384
His professional determination    
 and integrity set him apart

01:28:26.426 --> 01:28:30.388
as an outstanding example         
 for other officers,

01:28:30.430 --> 01:28:32.807
reserve and regular alike.

01:28:37.186 --> 01:28:39.939
He cannot be                      
 too highly commended."

01:28:45.320 --> 01:28:46.863
Thank you.

01:28:48.740 --> 01:28:50.450
No further questions.

01:28:54.829 --> 01:28:56.789
No cross-examination.

01:29:01.127 --> 01:29:03.004
You're excused,           
          Commander.

01:29:09.135 --> 01:29:10.678
Yes, sir.

01:29:30.198 --> 01:29:32.116
Defense rests.

01:29:34.369 --> 01:29:36.996
Is the trial counsel          
      ready for summation?

01:29:38.331 --> 01:29:41.000
No summary, sir.      
              Prosecution rests.

01:29:42.418 --> 01:29:44.212
No argument at all?

01:29:49.967 --> 01:29:52.178
If it please 
                      the court,

01:29:57.433 --> 01:29:59.644
I'm-- I'm at a loss

01:29:59.685 --> 01:30:02.522
to discuss the case           
      the defense has presented.

01:30:03.564 --> 01:30:05.483
I have nothing to refute.

01:30:05.525 --> 01:30:06.901
It's no case at all.

01:30:06.943 --> 01:30:08.528
It has nothing to do

01:30:08.569 --> 01:30:11.239
with the charge               
      or the specification.

01:30:13.032 --> 01:30:16.411
The defense counsel's         
      very first question           
      in this trial

01:30:17.620 --> 01:30:20.498
was, "Commander, have you         
 ever heard the expression,

01:30:20.540 --> 01:30:22.917
Old Yellowstain?"

01:30:22.959 --> 01:30:27.046
That was the key              
      to his entire strategy,

01:30:27.088 --> 01:30:30.007
which was simply to twist     
      the proceedings around

01:30:30.049 --> 01:30:34.262
so that the accused       
          would become not Maryk,   
          but Commander Queeg.

01:30:34.303 --> 01:30:38.015
He has dragged out        
          every possible vicious

01:30:38.057 --> 01:30:41.936
and malicious criticism   
          of the commander          
          from the other witnesses

01:30:41.978 --> 01:30:46.732
and forced Captain Queeg          
 to defend himself against them    
 in open court,

01:30:46.774 --> 01:30:48.609
on the spur of the moment,

01:30:48.651 --> 01:30:50.570
without advice of counsel,

01:30:50.611 --> 01:30:53.239
without any                   
      of the normal privileges      
      and safeguards

01:30:53.281 --> 01:30:56.325
of an accused man                 
 under naval law.

01:30:56.367 --> 01:30:59.787
Can this court possibly           
 endorse the precedent

01:30:59.829 --> 01:31:04.584
that a captain who doesn't        
 please his underlings             
 can be deposed by them?

01:31:04.625 --> 01:31:06.919
And then that the captain's       
 only recourse afterward

01:31:06.961 --> 01:31:11.799
is to be placed               
      at a witness stand            
      in a general court-martial

01:31:11.841 --> 01:31:13.968
to answer             
              every petty gripe

01:31:14.010 --> 01:31:16.262
and justify                   
      all his command decisions

01:31:16.304 --> 01:31:20.725
to a hostile lawyer           
      taking the part of            
      his insubordinate inferiors?

01:31:20.766 --> 01:31:24.645
Such a precedent is nothing       
 but a blank check for mutiny.

01:31:24.687 --> 01:31:28.232
It is the absolute destruction    
 of the chain of command.

01:31:30.985 --> 01:31:34.155
However,                      
      all this doesn't worry me.

01:31:35.031 --> 01:31:36.991
I am confident

01:31:37.033 --> 01:31:40.620
that this court               
      hasn't been impressed         
      by such aggressive tactics.

01:31:40.661 --> 01:31:43.080
I know that the court         
      is going to reject

01:31:43.122 --> 01:31:45.333
this cynical play             
      on its emotions,

01:31:45.374 --> 01:31:50.171
this... insult                
      to its intelligence,

01:31:50.213 --> 01:31:53.382
and find the specification    
      proven by the facts.

01:31:55.384 --> 01:31:57.386
I've only this to say.

01:31:58.387 --> 01:32:00.681
Whatever the verdict          
      on the accused, I--

01:32:01.766 --> 01:32:04.352
I formally recommend              
 that Defense Counsel Greenwald

01:32:04.393 --> 01:32:06.187
be censured by this court

01:32:06.229 --> 01:32:08.397
for conduct unbecoming        
      an officer of the Navy

01:32:08.439 --> 01:32:11.567
and that this reprimand       
      be made part of his record.

01:32:17.532 --> 01:32:20.576
Defense counsel.      
              Closing argument?

01:32:25.873 --> 01:32:27.208
Please the court,

01:32:28.543 --> 01:32:32.797
I undertook                   
      the defense of the accused    
      very reluctantly

01:32:32.838 --> 01:32:37.593
and only at the urging of         
 the judge advocate that no other 
 defense counsel was available.

01:32:38.553 --> 01:32:40.388
I was reluctant

01:32:40.429 --> 01:32:43.808
because I knew                
      that the only possible        
      form of defense

01:32:43.849 --> 01:32:47.812
was to prove                      
 the mental incompetence           
 of an officer of the Navy.

01:32:47.853 --> 01:32:53.317
It has been                       
 the most unpleasant duty          
 I have ever had to perform.

01:32:54.318 --> 01:32:57.363
However,                          
 once having undertaken it,

01:32:57.405 --> 01:32:59.532
I have done my best           
      to win an acquittal.

01:32:59.574 --> 01:33:03.369
I thought this was my duty,       
 both as defense counsel           
 appointed by the Navy

01:33:03.411 --> 01:33:06.205
and as a member of the bar.

01:33:07.456 --> 01:33:09.292
Let me make one thing clear.

01:33:09.333 --> 01:33:12.044
It is not the contention          
 of the defense

01:33:12.086 --> 01:33:14.213
that Commander Queeg              
 is a coward

01:33:14.255 --> 01:33:19.969
and that therefore,               
 if he commits questionable acts   
 under intense fire,

01:33:20.011 --> 01:33:22.888
the explanation                   
 must lie elsewhere.

01:33:22.930 --> 01:33:26.559
The court saw                 
      Commander Queeg's bearing     
      on the stand.

01:33:26.601 --> 01:33:30.062
The court can imagine     
          what his bearing          
          must have been like

01:33:30.104 --> 01:33:32.273
at the height     
                  of the storm.

01:33:32.315 --> 01:33:34.191
And on that basis,

01:33:35.234 --> 01:33:38.446
the court can decide      
          the fate of the accused.

01:33:44.619 --> 01:33:46.537
[exhales]

01:33:47.622 --> 01:33:49.874
Before recessing,

01:33:49.915 --> 01:33:52.460
the court will rule       
          on the recommendation     
          to censure you.

01:33:56.672 --> 01:33:58.132
Yes, sir.

01:34:00.635 --> 01:34:04.597
This has been a strange   
          and tragic trial.

01:34:05.681 --> 01:34:08.267
In the 248-year history   
          of the Navy,

01:34:08.309 --> 01:34:11.479
there has been only           
      one other attempted mutiny.

01:34:13.356 --> 01:34:16.776
You have conducted your case 
      with striking ingenuity.

01:34:18.569 --> 01:34:20.321
But your conduct          
          has been puzzling

01:34:20.363 --> 01:34:22.490
and it does raise questions.

01:34:23.491 --> 01:34:25.743
Has your conduct here         
      been responsible,

01:34:25.785 --> 01:34:27.495
Lieutenant Greenwald?

01:34:28.788 --> 01:34:30.414
[sighs]

01:34:30.456 --> 01:34:33.209
The reprimand,                
      if there is to be one,

01:34:33.250 --> 01:34:36.379
must come                     
      from your own conscience.

01:34:38.506 --> 01:34:42.343
Court finds defense counsel   
      has not been in contempt.

01:34:42.385 --> 01:34:45.304
Recommendation to reprimand   
      denied.

01:34:45.346 --> 01:34:48.140
Court stands in recess    
          until further notice.

01:34:48.182 --> 01:34:49.850
[gavel raps]

01:34:54.480 --> 01:34:57.692
What happens now?                 
                  Well, that's      
                  the ball game.

01:34:58.818 --> 01:35:00.194
And when do we find out?

01:35:00.236 --> 01:35:02.029
If it's an acquittal,     
          soon.

01:35:02.071 --> 01:35:05.533
If not, well,                 
      they won't publish            
      their findings for weeks.

01:35:05.574 --> 01:35:07.034
Okay.

01:35:08.035 --> 01:35:09.787
You were terrific.

01:35:09.829 --> 01:35:11.664
Thanks.

01:35:14.125 --> 01:35:16.377
You murdered Queeg                
 up there.

01:35:16.961 --> 01:35:19.255
Yes, I murdered him.

01:35:24.009 --> 01:35:27.680
I'm grateful to you,              
 win or lose.

01:35:32.476 --> 01:35:33.769
Okay.

01:35:36.522 --> 01:35:38.524
What's wrong?                     
              Not a thing.

01:35:38.566 --> 01:35:41.152
Well, look, I need to             
 ask you something.

01:35:41.193 --> 01:35:43.279
What now? Hmm?

01:35:44.947 --> 01:35:47.742
Tom Keefer's having a party       
 tonight at the hotel.

01:35:47.783 --> 01:35:50.745
This morning                      
 he got a $10,000 advance          
 on his novel.

01:35:50.786 --> 01:35:53.080
Well, I hope he sells     
          a million copies,

01:35:53.122 --> 01:35:56.417
wins the Nobel Prize,     
          the Pulitzer Prize,       
          the Medal of Honor.

01:35:56.459 --> 01:35:59.086
Wrap this whole thing up 
          in a nice, pink ribbon.

01:35:59.128 --> 01:36:00.838
We're both invited.

01:36:03.215 --> 01:36:04.759
What?

01:36:05.843 --> 01:36:08.471
Look, I know what                 
 you probably think.

01:36:08.512 --> 01:36:11.182
But one way or another,           
 it's over.

01:36:11.223 --> 01:36:14.268
I don't know                      
 what I would have done            
 in Tom's place.

01:36:14.310 --> 01:36:16.437
You'd go              
              to Keefer's party.

01:36:17.605 --> 01:36:20.775
I'll go if you will,              
 if you think we should.

01:36:33.204 --> 01:36:37.750
[pop music            
              playing on speakers]

01:36:43.130 --> 01:36:45.758
Oh!                           
                  [cheering]

01:36:53.307 --> 01:36:55.601
All right, quiet, quiet!

01:36:55.643 --> 01:36:56.727
[whistles]

01:36:56.769 --> 01:36:59.730
Quiet, you drunken bums       
      of the   Caine!

01:36:59.772 --> 01:37:03.901
Here he is,               
          the guest of honor,       
          our courageous hero.

01:37:03.943 --> 01:37:05.069
Hey!                          
                      Whoo!

01:37:05.110 --> 01:37:07.112
Speech!                   
          Speech, speech, speech!

01:37:07.154 --> 01:37:10.449
[all chanting]                
      Speech! Speech! Speech!       
      No, no, no, no.

01:37:10.491 --> 01:37:13.828
No, no, no, no, no, no!           
              Come on, Barney!

01:37:13.869 --> 01:37:16.872
No, I-I-I'm drunker               
 than any of you guys.             
              [laughing]

01:37:16.914 --> 01:37:19.041
I've been out                     
 with the trial counsel,

01:37:19.083 --> 01:37:22.044
trying to get her to take back    
 some of the dirty names           
 she called me.

01:37:22.086 --> 01:37:24.338
[all chuckle]

01:37:24.380 --> 01:37:27.842
I finally got her to shake hands 
 on the third bourbon and soda,    
 maybe the fourth.

01:37:27.883 --> 01:37:30.928
That's good. That's good.     
 I had to talk loud and fast,      
 Steve.

01:37:30.970 --> 01:37:34.306
I played some pretty              
 dirty pool in court.              
 Well...

01:37:34.348 --> 01:37:36.100
Poor Katherine Challee, huh?      
 Yeah.

01:37:36.141 --> 01:37:38.352
Mmm. So what's this?

01:37:38.394 --> 01:37:40.396
[Maryk] Oh, it's          
          a double celebration.

01:37:40.437 --> 01:37:41.981
[Greenwald]                       
 A cake baked like a book.

01:37:42.022 --> 01:37:44.233
$10,000                       
      came in the mail today.       
      Advance on my novel.

01:37:44.275 --> 01:37:46.235
[all cheering]

01:37:46.277 --> 01:37:48.445
Very nice.                
          Very nice.

01:37:48.487 --> 01:37:49.905
I got something               
      in the mail today too.

01:37:49.947 --> 01:37:52.616
What's that, Barney?              
          Medical clearance.

01:37:52.658 --> 01:37:55.202
Orders back to my ship.   
          Leaving tomorrow.

01:37:55.244 --> 01:37:56.370
[all cheering]

01:37:56.412 --> 01:37:58.956
Good.                 
              Hey, that's great.

01:38:01.083 --> 01:38:02.376
Ten thousand bucks,           
      huh?

01:38:02.418 --> 01:38:04.420
[whistles]

01:38:05.588 --> 01:38:07.006
You know,                     
      maybe I should

01:38:07.047 --> 01:38:09.592
return                        
      the celebrated author's       
      toast.

01:38:09.633 --> 01:38:11.260
Yes!                              
      A little, little speech.

01:38:11.302 --> 01:38:13.888
All right, all right, all right. 
 Here we go, here we go.

01:38:13.929 --> 01:38:15.514
Okay.                     
 [chuckles]

01:38:15.556 --> 01:38:18.017
Uh, war novel, isn't it?          
                  That's right.

01:38:18.058 --> 01:38:20.936
I assume you gave the Navy        
 a good screwing, yeah?

01:38:20.978 --> 01:38:22.980
Yeah?                             
 [all laughing]

01:38:23.022 --> 01:38:25.357
I don't think                     
 that Navy Public Affairs          
 would approve it at any rate.

01:38:25.399 --> 01:38:28.569
Well, somebody                    
 should show up these stupid,      
 stuffy old pricks, huh?

01:38:28.611 --> 01:38:31.155
Yeah!                             
      Who's the hero, you?

01:38:31.196 --> 01:38:34.158
If there's any similarities, 
      it is purely coincidental.

01:38:34.199 --> 01:38:36.368
[crowd chuckles]

01:38:36.410 --> 01:38:39.371
Okay, I'm warped              
      and I'm drunk.

01:38:40.789 --> 01:38:43.751
But it suddenly seems to me,      
 if I wrote a war novel,

01:38:43.792 --> 01:38:46.587
I would try to make a hero        
 out of Old Yellowstain.

01:38:46.629 --> 01:38:48.505
Mmm.                              
 Oh, come on.

01:38:48.547 --> 01:38:49.965
That's right, I would.        
 No. No.

01:38:50.007 --> 01:38:52.426
No, I would.                  
      And I'll tell you why.

01:38:53.636 --> 01:38:56.305
You see, Mr. Keefer,              
 while I was studying law

01:38:56.347 --> 01:38:58.015
and you were                      
 writing short stories,

01:38:58.057 --> 01:39:00.768
and Willie Keith                  
 was playing on the fields         
 of Princeton,

01:39:00.809 --> 01:39:04.021
why, all that time,           
      these--

01:39:04.063 --> 01:39:06.899
these old birds                   
 we call regulars,                 
 these stupid, stuffy pricks,

01:39:06.941 --> 01:39:08.692
were standing guard

01:39:08.734 --> 01:39:12.947
on our fat, dumb                  
 and happy country.

01:39:13.948 --> 01:39:16.450
Of course, they were              
 doing it for dough.

01:39:16.492 --> 01:39:18.452
Same as anybody does anything.

01:39:19.453 --> 01:39:23.082
But the question is,          
      in the last analysis...

01:39:24.208 --> 01:39:26.669
I mean,                       
      what do you do for dough?     
      You and me.

01:39:26.710 --> 01:39:30.464
We're advancing               
      our free little careers.

01:39:31.924 --> 01:39:36.220
So when 9/11 happened         
      and so many of us             
      rushed to join up

01:39:36.261 --> 01:39:40.599
to fight those assholes       
      that crashed those planes     
      into the Twin Towers...

01:39:42.351 --> 01:39:45.396
You couldn't fight them       
      with a law book,              
      so I-- I went active.

01:39:45.437 --> 01:39:47.022
I joined the Navy.

01:39:48.357 --> 01:39:50.109
Maybe I'd fly over            
      the Middle East

01:39:50.150 --> 01:39:52.152
and bomb the shit             
      out of some terrorists,       
      right?

01:39:52.194 --> 01:39:54.363
Whoo!                             
 [crowd chuckling]

01:39:54.405 --> 01:39:58.951
But there were already        
      a lot of guys                 
      ready to do that.

01:40:00.285 --> 01:40:02.579
And it wasn't me.             
      Not yet.

01:40:02.621 --> 01:40:05.082
Wasn't Tom Keefer,            
      still in school,

01:40:05.124 --> 01:40:07.793
or Willie Keith               
      in midshipman training,

01:40:07.835 --> 01:40:11.714
but Old Yellowstain           
      and guys like him.

01:40:12.798 --> 01:40:15.384
They were already on station,     
 ready to go.

01:40:16.552 --> 01:40:18.345
And they're a lot smarter     
      than any of us.

01:40:18.387 --> 01:40:21.015
I mean, let's-- Come on.          
 Let's not kid ourselves.

01:40:21.056 --> 01:40:25.436
I mean, you don't get anywhere    
 in the all-volunteer,             
 upwardly mobile American Navy

01:40:25.477 --> 01:40:27.271
unless you're goddamn good.

01:40:28.814 --> 01:40:31.859
And these old-line pros,          
 they may not be up                
 on the latest video game,

01:40:31.900 --> 01:40:34.361
but they know how                 
 to get a tough job done.

01:40:35.487 --> 01:40:39.158
And they were standing by,        
 and they were ready to do it,

01:40:39.199 --> 01:40:41.744
while the rest of us              
 were still trying to              
 know shit from Shinola.

01:40:41.785 --> 01:40:44.705
Barney. Hey, Barney. 
              It's over.

01:40:44.747 --> 01:40:46.707
All right? Come on.       
          Let's just enjoy dinner.

01:40:46.749 --> 01:40:49.209
Dinner's a sham, Steve.       
      You're guilty.

01:40:50.753 --> 01:40:53.380
Of course,                        
 you're only half guilty.

01:40:53.422 --> 01:40:56.884
I mean, there was someone else    
 standing very neatly              
 out of the picture,

01:40:57.801 --> 01:40:59.720
the guy who started           
      the whole idea

01:40:59.762 --> 01:41:01.513
that Queeg's                  
      a dangerous paranoiac,

01:41:01.555 --> 01:41:04.058
who argued you into it        
      for six months,

01:41:04.099 --> 01:41:06.727
who coined the nickname           
 Old Yellowstain,

01:41:06.769 --> 01:41:10.814
who pointed out the psychiatry    
 books and Article 1108            
 and kept hammering it at you.

01:41:10.856 --> 01:41:12.357
All right,                    
      wait a minute here.

01:41:12.399 --> 01:41:15.527
Oh, yeah, yeah, Mr. Keefer.       
 That's right, yeah.

01:41:16.361 --> 01:41:18.489
I had to drag it              
      out of Steve.

01:41:18.530 --> 01:41:21.700
Big dumb Polack               
      tried to tell me              
      it was all his own idea.

01:41:21.742 --> 01:41:25.662
He wouldn't know a paranoid       
 from an anthropoid.               
 But you knew, didn't you?

01:41:25.704 --> 01:41:31.251
You told him his medical log      
 was a clinical picture            
 of a paranoid.

01:41:31.293 --> 01:41:34.588
You advised him                   
 to go to Admiral Williams.        
 You offered to go with him.

01:41:34.630 --> 01:41:39.093
You didn't get cold feet          
 until you stood on Williams's     
 quarterdeck in Bahrain.

01:41:39.134 --> 01:41:41.720
Yeah, and then you ducked,        
 and you've been ducking           
 ever since.

01:41:41.762 --> 01:41:43.597
I don't know              
          where you're              
          getting all this.

01:41:43.639 --> 01:41:45.724
Biggest favor                 
      you could have done Steve,

01:41:45.766 --> 01:41:47.726
as far as winning         
          an acquittal went,

01:41:47.768 --> 01:41:49.728
though I doubt            
          you realize it.

01:41:51.939 --> 01:41:54.858
But if there is           
          a guilty party,           
          it's you.

01:41:56.318 --> 01:41:59.780
If you hadn't filled          
      Steve Maryk's thick head

01:41:59.822 --> 01:42:01.448
full of paranoia                  
 and Article 1108,

01:42:01.490 --> 01:42:05.285
why, he'd have--                  
 he'd have got Queeg               
 to come north.

01:42:05.327 --> 01:42:08.956
Or he'd have helped him       
      pull through to the south.

01:42:10.290 --> 01:42:12.960
And the   Caine   wouldn't have   
      been yanked out of action.

01:42:13.001 --> 01:42:14.753
And that--

01:42:14.795 --> 01:42:17.631
that is your contribution

01:42:17.673 --> 01:42:19.967
to the good old USA,      
          my friend--

01:42:20.008 --> 01:42:23.470
pulling a minesweeper         
      out of the Persian Gulf       
      when it was most needed.

01:42:23.512 --> 01:42:26.265
That-- That...                    
 [laughs] ...and fucking           
 Multitudes, Multitudes.

01:42:26.306 --> 01:42:27.474
You're drunk.

